Ok, Sylvain, sorry I was not clear when set you -1 last patch set. I meant the following:

1/ If we are creating classes, we use CamelCase (e.g. VeryLongClassName)
2/ If we are creating variables, we use lower_case_with_underscores (e.g. very_long_variable_name)

So your class names were really OK, you may leave them as is. So I propose

1/ Classes names: ComputeHostReservation, ComputeHostExtraCapability (as they were in your code from the very beginning)
2/ Variable names: compute_host_reservations, compute_host_extra_capabilities

Logic for variable naming is the same as for the classes naming (each word in name should be somehow separated from others, by capital letter in the class names, by '_' in the variable names)

Also I really will appreciate if you will use compute_host, not computehost, because still there are two words, and separating them will increase readability.

Sorry one more time for vague description of what I wanted last patch set.

For more info about namings http://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0008/#prescriptive-naming-conventions"}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2013-12-06 14:02:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-03 20:44:09.000000000', 'message': 'DB API and models for supporting Compute Hosts Reservations

As per our design doc for Hosts reservations [1], Climate needs to be
added three new models called ComputeHost, ComputeHostExtraCapabilities
and ComputeHostReservation

 * ComputeHost will store all info concerning hosts managed by Climate
   and will keep tracability on if they are free for a lease or not
 * ComputeHostExtraCapabilities will allow admin user to add extra info
   for each host to add to Climate like GPU or SSD which are not yet
   visible thru Nova-Compute
 * ComputeHostReservation will store all reservation details when
   creating a lease, needed by Manager when starting the lease

Implements bp:host-db-api

[1] : https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1-_DOB65LsSGR4JUaPN525bWAg1yhvEv3KNcHfmuLvYw/edit

Change-Id: Ib8f289064a9621372908be1d44db92f3719b24e1

commit_message:
DB API and models for supporting Compute Hosts Reservations

As per our design doc for Hosts reservations [1], Climate needs to be
added three new models called ComputeHost, ComputeHostExtraCapabilities
and ComputeHostReservation

 * ComputeHost will store all info concerning hosts managed by Climate
   and will keep tracability on if they are free for a lease or not
 * ComputeHostExtraCapabilities will allow admin user to add extra info
   for each host to add to Climate like GPU or SSD which are not yet
   visible thru Nova-Compute
 * ComputeHostReservation will store all reservation details when
   creating a lease, needed by Manager when starting the leases

Implements bp:host-db-api

[1] : https://docs.google.com/drawings/d/1-_DOB65LsSGR4JUaPN525bWAg1yhvEv3KNcHfmuLvYw/edit

Change-Id: Ib8f289064a9621372908be1d44db92f3719b24e1

commit_message:
Use code from AdvNetworking for MS SQL Cluster IP validation.

Use code borrowed from murano-conductor for generation of subnets
against which both MS SQL Cluster IPs should be validated (they should
belong to that subnet). Old validation of static IPs is no longer
sufficient because CIDR's are generated by murano-conductor during
deployment.

Valid subnet, once generated in dashboard for validation purposes, is
stored in murano-api environment for later use by murano-conductor
(DRY). So this commit comes in a team with 2 following commits:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59982/ and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/59983/

Change-Id: I02c1b1905dd15535f807bcbc49b4f8fc2ad435d7

commit_message:
Set include_service_catalog to False

include_service_catalog is a parameter in swift authtoken configuration.
Set to False improves performances.

Closes-Bug #1257738
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

Change-Id: Ie5dd2de45fce79e4da7ccb5b37d7c69ee1cb5198

[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-09 23:56:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-tripleo-incubator-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/68/60968/1/check/gate-tripleo-incubator-docs/04f0f1f/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 28s
'}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2013-12-09 23:57:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I am concerned that in the long run there will be confusion between this, which will be used to configure an environment even when we don't want to build or start the seed VM at this stage, and use of a cached image which is already supported in the script.

Suggestions welcome."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-10 03:34:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

Ok, so there are really three steps here:

 A - create a VM definition
 B - create an image suitable for use in a VM
 C - boot that image in that VM

boot-seed-vm was a helper to do all three but...

with CI we want:

 - the test environment to do A
 - the test running environment to do B
 - to copy the image to the test environment before doing C remotely

I suggest we split this up into three bits - and do this in devtest too :)

 - A - configure the vm - do this before devtest_undercloud - part of the init stuff
 - B - just use DIB directly, get rid of the layering
 - C - call this from dev_seed, have it do the copy + the virsh commands (and we'll need some remote virsh support - perhaps via the broker?) to trigger this on the TE host."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-12-10 03:35:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

-1 cause of the n/i typo."}, {'account_id': 7144, 'date': '2013-12-10 03:46:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I like lifeless's idea about breaking this up.

Otherwise, in the short term, there's a small typo in the help text for the new option."}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2013-12-10 06:26:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

Thanks lifeless, that's pretty much how I understood it too.

I've fixed up the noted typos, uploading change now."}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2013-12-10 06:26:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-10 06:27:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

It seems fairly trivial to me to split out the image building bits into build-seed-vm

Next step would be to make devtest use build-seed-vm and boot-seed-vm -i

And then we can remove the image building bits from boot-seed-vm (and eventually the -i option)'}, {'account_id': 8449, 'date': '2013-12-10 07:33:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

commit_message:
Add image already exists option to boot-seed-vm

Add an option to indicate that the image to be used does not need
to be built at this stage.

This differs from a cached image that lives on the disk during
this step.

Change-Id: I0672e2ae20e81b9edef328cc6f71a2a32e8b4707

You should update original change request to resolve all comments in that review:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/60420/1

It is needed because if original CR will not have all resolved comments it will not merged eventually and all 'Needed By' CRs will not merged as well. If you'd like to send new CR to resolve some comments you should notify all reviewers in the original CR. But I'd recommend you to resolve all comments in the single change request.

The actual command how to update original CR with newe changes is "git commit --amend" on original CR.

oslo-incubator.

The fix is the following oslo-incubator commit:

  76972e2 Support a new qpid topology

This includes one other commit, so that the above fix could be brought
in cleanly:

Closes-bug: #1178375

commit_message:
Backport some rpc fixes

There is no specific patches from master that can be backported to fix
this bug because the fix is tied up with a much larger sync of rpc from
oslo-incubator.

The fix is the following oslo-incubator commit:

  76972e2 Support a new qpid topology

This includes one other commit, so that the above fix could be brought
in cleanly:

  5ff534d Add config for amqp durable/auto_delete queues

Change-Id: Ib5f6eddc4813a3c755d871f486c66bd66093ded4
Closes-bug: #1178375

commit_message:
Prevent rescheduling on block device failure

Due to a race condition - it is possible for more instances to race for
the same volume. In such a scenario, the one that fails will get
rescheduled, and in the process detach the volume of a successful
instance.

To prevent this, this patch makes nova not reschedule on block device
failures. This is actually reasonable behaviour as block device failures
are rarely related to the compute host itself and so rescheduling is not
usually useful.

This is a stable/havana only fix! This same issue is addressed on the
master branch by Iefab71047996b7cc08107794d5bc628c11680a70.

Closes-bug: 1195947

Change-Id: I6b68965ac65cdb0e1da3b44e83428f056b1693aa

commit_message:
Use files in the source tree instead of cut/paste

Many of the large files are included in the tree and the script now
leverages a checked out swift tree to provide those files so that
users don't have to cut/paste text from the document. The contents of
those files are still included in the document for reference.

Updated to add sudo in appropriate places so that the entire script
can be run as the user instead of as root.

We also simplify the steps needed to get resetswift script working
(don't need to edit the user name).

Change-Id: Ie5b5a815870edcc205d273e35e0bbd2426d3b002
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Add attributes schema to OS::Neutron::FloatingIP

FloatingIP now validates attributes against a schema instead of
accepting all possible inputs and filtering on the result returned by
neutron.

Change-Id: I3bf1c3728a9d6faab71c2312f331d73b1460c013
Closes-Bug: #1240893

While I have no real objection to this, I also do not understand the utility.  I get how it adds some code coverage to the tests suite but it does not seem to be actually testing any behavior at all.  It seems that all that happens is every call in main is mocked out, and then we verify that the calls were made in that order.  I am having a hard time seeing what regression or bug this will trap.  In other words, how do these tests help us ensure that no future bugs will slip into cache_cleaner?"}, {'account_id': 6493, 'date': '2013-09-19 00:36:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I have a similar comment in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46064/.  This test gives us coverage, but what behavior does it test?

also, does this need to depend on 46064?'}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2013-09-19 01:30:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Same concerns as jbresnah. Seems everything is mocked and we're just verifying the invoking order. So would you mind taking an example to clarify what kind of bug will be caught by this coverage? And it would be nice if a bug can be opened to associate with this patch. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 8689, 'date': '2013-09-19 12:27:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

As I can see, code in cache_cleaner.py has two goals:
1. Prepare required conditions and run cache cleaner.
2. Catch RuntimeErrors and call system exit with the exception details. 

So to test this module we need two tests. The first one should verify that all conditions are prepared before running the Cleaner. And then it should verify that Cleaner was actually started. The second one should verify that exceptions handling was implemented. As the code was developed without unit tests I only added unit tests missed during development.

What issues they can prevent in future? If a developer refactors the code, adds come preconditions, changes/removes exception handling, due to these unit tests they have to doublecheck, if their changes break some original call sequence.
I mocked all internall calls because it's another logic that is not a point to check in these tests. For example, why do I need to ckeck parsing arguments if I want to verify, if it was called before running cleaner and not after. And so on."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-27 06:03:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Tests added for glance/cmd/cache_cleaner.py

Integration test test_cache_cleaner_main added to cover
chain of calls between glance/cmd/cache_cleaner.py and glance/image_cache
module.
Unit test test_cache_cleaner_main_runtime_exception_handling added to
cover exception handling for main() method of cache_cleaner.py

Change-Id: Ic05f35dd3f0a93d4331ccb5e470cdb71d9eab605

commit_message:
WSDL caching service for SOAP drivers

SOAP SUDS drivers may benefit from local caching of WSDL files.
Support classes add hooks for WSDL "repair" actions.

Change-Id: If88e23a8132b788b8c32bfa0b666029667912894
Blueprint: autowsdl-caching

commit_message:
Add static IPv6 injection scenario testcase

Now Neutron has supported injecting a static IPv6 address into the
instances, this commit cover a scenario testcase to validate the
function.

Note. assume that image and interfaces.template file only have IPv6 section.

Change-Id: I7b5506a6669fd5a870723209fead443de4cb4ef2

VPNaas IPSec Site Connection API tests

commit_message:
fix split path in handling REPLICATE

When handling REPLICATE request, (account|container) server use the
wrong value for 'hsh' varible (container server will fail when spliting
its path). This patch uses hash_path function to generate correct hsh to
replicator_rpc.dispatch.

Change-Id: I9e698b51215adec4e52cae47fbd54c614259a4cb

[{'created': '2013-12-02 20:27:26.000000000', 'message': "Trap failures due to old easy_install

In some old setuptools/easy_install installations with setup.py install,
easy_install winds up being none (please don't ask me why) which means
that the call to get the script header winds up being broken. If you're
in that env, then being clever with script headers is a waste.

Change-Id: I43dac981fadd31e00010b8073fc5f503aaadfce8
"}, {'created': '2013-12-02 20:32:22.000000000', 'message': "Trap failures due to old easy_install

In some old setuptools/easy_install installations with setup.py install,
easy_install winds up being none (please don't ask me why) which means
that the call to get the script header winds up being broken. If you're
in that env, then being clever with script headers is a waste.

Change-Id: I43dac981fadd31e00010b8073fc5f503aaadfce8
"}]
commit_message:
Trap failures due to old easy_install

In some old setuptools/easy_install installations with setup.py install,
easy_install winds up being none (please don't ask me why) which means
that the call to get the script header winds up being broken. If you're
in that env, then being clever with script headers is a waste.

Change-Id: I43dac981fadd31e00010b8073fc5f503aaadfce8

Third party GUIs may rely on notifications to track the
progress of volume creation and deletion.  In the case that
a volume is being deleted after a failed attempt to create
(the volume is listed in the database but is not actually
resident in a backing store) the path that is taken in
volume.api.delete() makes no notifications of deletion
occurring.

This patch adds a volume_utils.notify_about_volume_usage
call to the beginning and end of the delete with a
delete.start and delete.end respectively.  The notifications
serve as triggers for GUIs to refresh the state of the

Closes-Bug: 1257053

commit_message:
delete.start/delete.end notification for hostless

Third party GUIs may rely on notifications to track the
progress of volume creation and deletion.  In the case that
a volume is being deleted after a failed attempt to create
(the volume is listed in the database but is not actually
resident in a backing store) the path that is taken in
volume.api.delete() makes no notifications of deletion
occurring.

This patch adds a volume_utils.notify_about_volume_usage
call to the beginning and end of the delete with a
delete.start and delete.end respectively.  The notifications
serve as triggers for GUIs to refresh the state of the
volume.  This change makes the hostless delete path's
functionality more consistent with the other paths through
the delete code.

Change-Id: I091b9d277834b341105569d41a48ef5c1fc105ce
Closes-Bug: 1257053

The glusterfs_disk_util option lets one choose whether to
use df or du to calculate space usage.  This serves no real
useful purpose.  Should remove this option to simplify things.

Since this does not meaningfully impact behavior, removal of
this option shouldn't require any special deprecation efforts.

(This same change was made for the NFS driver in 5bf7b9be.)

DocImpact: Remove config option

Change-Id: I302692454b43de15688d65873a72a3dada0c67cb
"}]
commit_message:
GlusterFS: Remove glusterfs_disk_util option

The glusterfs_disk_util option lets one choose whether to
use df or du to calculate space usage.  This serves no real
useful purpose.  Should remove this option to simplify things.

Since this does not meaningfully impact behavior, removal of
this option shouldn't require any special deprecation efforts.

(This same change was made for the NFS driver in 5bf7b9be.)

DocImpact: Remove config option

Change-Id: I302692454b43de15688d65873a72a3dada0c67cb

commit_message:
Catch TypeError when new_size is None on extend

The volume_actions extend method does not catch/handle TypeError
exceptions.  The tempest volume_actions test includes a negative
test that doesn't pass in a new-size so the result is we get an
unhandled exception/trace in the log files for these runs.

Change-Id: I8b699a28e06e62126da02c3318d3129412dffa6b
Closes-Bug: #1259336

I wonder wouldn't be better to create new tenant at runtime with a "hard coded" expected limits for the quota tests.'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-11-25 09:59:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hmm i think you may be right especially if we want to support also a deployment that use -1 as default quota, i.e. unlimited.'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-11-28 12:08:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@afazekas: I forgot about the case when allow_tenant_isolation is False ! i think we can't relay on the fact of being able to create an isolated tenant for test case.

BTW i still would like to support -1 as default quota, but i am not sure if we should just skip this test or what !?"}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-12-03 05:51:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

You can create a tenant even if the tenant isolation is false, you just need admin credentials.

The quota related test usually requires admin assistance even if we just use not admin user for allocating the resources.

I know it can be problematic, if someone does not wants to use admin credentials for quota tests. 
Is it your concern ?

There are several future thing which can mitigate the admin credentials requirements:
- keystone v3 -> just use domain admin instead of "the god" admin
- use multiple predefined users (or user pair) (new type of isolation for multi-process  parallel testing)

However neither of them makes possible all quota related test without a true admin permission.
And does not makes all tests run-able, (we will need more flags)

In this case a configurable skip sounds reasonable.'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-12-03 10:36:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

similar change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/57392/'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-03 15:23:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> You can create a tenant even if the tenant isolation is false, you just need admin credentials.

I know that i can, but wouldn't be un ethical to do that if user asked nicely that he doesn't want "tenant isolation" :) ?

My concern is that if user say no tenant isolation so we should respect that, no other tenant should be created except the one that user did create to run tempest i.e. the one that he had to fill in tempest.conf.

At least this is how i understood tenant_isolation: "Allows test cases to create/destroy tenants and users".'}, {'account_id': 7882, 'date': '2013-12-04 05:16:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(3 inline comments)

Hi, Mouad.
Sorry, I committed a similar patch without knowing your patch.
So, I will abandon my patch and follow this patch.
This is the advice from David Kranz : "This in the case where the quota in a real system might be very large. The quota tests for other projects first set the quota to a very small value, even zero, and then try. Would that be a better approach here as well?"
I would prefer that making this test switch DO/DON'T by conf file or something, How do you think?'}, {'account_id': 7139, 'date': '2013-12-04 06:05:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

"}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-04 10:07:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

> This in the case where the quota in a real system might be very large. 

IMHO i don't see this as a problem, i see it as a good think actually, if i set the quota to 10**7 + 9 i would like to see if tempest can detect whether people can create more than 10**7 + 9, which also mean that i would like to see whether i can create 10**7 + 9 network/port/subnet, right ?

> The quota tests for other projects first set the quota to a very small value, even zero, and then try.

Sure it will take more time to do so but i don't think we should set quota to a small value b/c it's like telling tempest user, we did test quota and we saw that you can't create more than quota limit, and now what do you think the user will think ? if it was me i will say: "hmm i set quota to 10**7 + 9 and i am sure now, thanks to tempest, that we can create up to 10**7+9 network and no more :)", but if we do it this way i will hate tempest b/c it did lie to me, it didn't test the quota limit that i set (as a deployer) it tested his quota limit :( (this tempest for validating a deployment use case), OOTH there is also user that doesn't want tempest to spend ages doing this .... 

> I would prefer that making this test switch DO/DON'T by conf file or something, How do you think?

Actually we were discussing the same thing in this patch about when quota is -1 i.e. unlimited, -1 is detectable by code and we can raise SkipTest for it and it's doesn't make sense to test quota in this case at all, but for big quota limit i am still not sure what can we do !? if it's an option in the config what will be the default ? maybe a better approach is to have a threshold of what is to big to skip !? 

Any thoughts ?'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-05 09:16:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-06 18:05:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Yuiko: Don't abandon your patch i am abandoning mine."}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-06 18:05:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 7882, 'date': '2013-12-10 04:55:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi, mouad. I'm so sorry for I couldn't comment because my PC was broken.
Because of that you had to abandon your patch.
I will manage my patch responsibly."}]

commit_message:
Make quota scenario test case more generic

Instead of assuming that the openstack deployment use default quota
for port, network and subnets it's better to just get the actual
quota using the API.

Change-Id: I29a2cfc4a2b27d6108890ae68aa2ec3dffd04534
Closes-Bug: #1249275

commit_message:
Sync matchmaker_ring.py from oslo-incubator

Cinder does not currently include the matchmaker driver, which is the
preferred configuration with ZeroMQ.

commit_message:
Glance image-list failed when image number exceed DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE

The root cause of the problem is that DB2 does not allow
an empty string ('') for datetime field. So we set the
default value of datetime as None.

Fixes bug 1245947

Change-Id: Ie372efe70a068024298fbde4574e33e565cc6c9a

commit_message:
Remove redundant whitelist for DHCP agent

It looks like the whitelist for the DHCP agent is added
twice. This looks like a genuine typo, and if it isn't
there is clearly something wrong! There's no good reason
for duplicating the list of whitelisted errors.

Change-Id: Ib94f60e8aa3ce1b0a6e28d9051da0124d403bf27

commit_message:
Fix null value of password on hash_user_password

"password" is optional parameter when create a user. If create a user with
the null value of password the HTTP 400 (ValidationError) exception
raised. Because the server has to check the length of the password when
hash the password, the TypeError be catched and be transfered to
ValidationError.

First there is no need to hash the null value. Second "password" para
should be treated as other optional para such as "tenantId", the server
should not raise exception with the null value.

The patch fixes the null value situation for "password" para.

Change-Id: I7c7bd356b336a213dffc7797a5f459cfbb2d50da
Closes-Bug: #1256491

commit_message:
Add config option for # of conductor replicas

Add hash_distribution_replicas option to ironic.common.hash_ring.

The consistent hash ring supports mapping to additional nodes around the
ring if some nodes may be temporarily offline. This option determines
how many nodes should be prepared in advance.

blueprint instance-mapping-by-consistent-hash

Change-Id: I93c2f735e201bbfb266e5a637fc76ddd5ca90e87

commit_message:
Skip sniffing and reseting if retry is disabled

Bypass sniffing entirely if retries has been disabled.

Fix bug #1216981

Change-Id: I593bdc56ca139af5a7f2ca2783ef2de2a96c94fb
Signed-off-by: Yuan Zhou <yuan.zhou@intel.com>

commit_message:
Add RBD test for volume not existing during delete

For cases when the volume does not exist in the backend, but Cinder
still knows about it, we just return from the rbd driver and let Cinder
do its thing.

Change-Id: I6150756bdd48259ec8d550fa7a5dc7a9f882ca22

commit_message:
Replace unicode with six.text_type for python3 compatibility

Python 2âs unicode() type was renamed str() in Python 3, str() was
renamed bytes(), and basestring() disappeared. six provides tools
to deal with these changes.

Implements: blueprint migrate-unicode-to-six

Change-Id: I73deb9f4296c8b1ee675fdf09b620353af777f28

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore to ignore *.egg*

Reasons:
 - pbr-*.egg* is created during tox testing
 - To ignore any package being generated in future

Changes:
 - *.egg* is added in .gitignore
 - python_troveclient.egg* is removed as *.egg*
   takes care of this too.

Change-Id: Ib66bdca8d8d632e88e22cc533d7591613b87123b
Closes-Bug: #1259221

commit_message:
Python3 support for xmlrpclib

Python3 actually does include xmlrpc(lib). It's just called
xmlrpc.client. The class and function signatures are the
same as the old Python2.x xmlrpclib module.

Adds a note that six.moves should be used once six 1.4.2 is
released. See http://bit.ly/1bqrVzu.

References:

Python 2 xmprpllib doc: http://docs.python.org/2/library/xmlrpclib.html
Python 3 xmlrpc.client doc: http://docs.python.org/3/library/xmlrpc.client.html

Change-Id: I478b56f22d02350a21093a887d9f6fcb84958724

commit_message:
Fixed docstring.

The docstring in Component and Service classes had incorrect
grammar. The docstring in Component class was not following
OpenStack HACKING style guide. Fixed both these issues.

Change-Id: Id057851dbc88977b0dbeef3f990585f7fdbb94e5

commit_message:
Remove root_helper config from plugin ini

As root_helper is defined in neutron.conf, root_helper in plugin ini
is unnecessary and brings confusion when configuring the parameter.
This patch updates plugin ini of NEC plugin and Brocade plugin.

Change-Id: I5b1c36d8d6ffc20ae0b4191a73aaa51f2b3d9a1b
Closes-Bug: #1259242

commit_message:
Allow intrinsic functions to be called in any order

An optional transform function can be passed into the resolve
functions, which allows transforms to occur on the child snippets.

Change-Id: I5d9e061c6a55f3939c5e03c780eaad72a001fccc
Closes-Bug: #1256742

Add mock to test-requirements.txt

mock is used by the oslo incubator test fixtures in mockpatch. So this
patch ensures it gets installed by adding it to the test requirements
list.

commit_message:
LVM migration: Check if name is equal to dest_vg

The existence check of the destination volume group is wrong. It
currently checks if there's a VG with a name equal to the source's vg
name instead of checking if it's equal to the dest_vg.

Closes-bug: #1258203
Change-Id: Ia5d4acb24b94c6aa832107c7eb4b6996985af97f

commit_message:
Remove the largely obsolete basepath helper

Now that there is a static method for calculating the path to the
config drive, there was only one user left for basepath, and it was
a special case "no filename" user. So, remove it.

Change-Id: I8f4efe19da41d159e929853a5e757e0e168885d7

commit_message:
Install guide: don't duplicate AMQP configuration

The nova-network section redefines the rabbit_host option. This doesn't
hurt but might lead to problems if the user wants to change the settings
later.

Change-Id: I71481813c77dfa40ca664e99afe7885141b6361f
backport: havana
(cherry picked from commit 510d0901ea5161a5e562334275399b1ec7b6509e)

commit_message:
Correct the port group defined location in vmware guide

The right port group defined location is section [DEFAULT]
"neutron_ovs_bridge=" in file nova.conf, if using vcenter
driver with OpenStack Networking Service and OVS agent.

Change-Id: I9430afa843cc44694b7aca11793ec0fb640b49c6
(cherry picked from commit 40ec040797b98444d6a1d7eb0bd614f7bd9338c2)

commit_message:
Install guide: recommend 64-bit OS

Add some text to the install guide to recommend installing a 64-bit
operating system. Also links to Ops Guide for system requirements.

Motivated by this comment in the docs:
http://docs.openstack.org/havana/install-guide/install/apt/content/nova-boot.html#comment-1146233396

commit_message:
Fix refresh firewall always called in linuxbridge agent

refresh_firewall() was being called for ports that had no
security groups due to a mistake in the check for that.

Change-Id: I6d7b394fefe2d544e1a4eaef399b2744355d3456
Closes-Bug: 1259268

commit_message:
Make consumer_for a context manager

This patch converts consumer_for into a `contextmanager` decorated
method and adapts `__getattribute__` to support this change. A new
method was not added to avoid clashes with method names in the stages.

Change-Id: I6c0727e86d9ee8d6bd34c312d180040c8baf34ba

commit_message:
fix: Reduce logging severity of certain errors

Here are the proposed changes:
- OverflowedJsonInteger: exception -> debug
- InvalidJson: exception -> debug
- InvalidQueueName: warning -> debug

Rationale: these pollute the server logs and provide little value to
system operators.

Change-Id: Icd73a5bd3fc7d7ef349b18e7e485df8a7dfc0a1a
Closes-Bug: #1246977

commit_message:
Remove the __MARCONI_SETUP_ global from init

This was used to know when Marconi was being loaded and avoid
registering configuration options and doing other things. This is not
necessary anymore.

Change-Id: Icf43302581eefb563b10ddec5831eeec0d068872
Partially-Implements: py3k-support

commit_message:
Use relative import for base in tests

Py3K fails to import base for tests. Use a relative import instead of an
absolute one.

Partially-implements: py3k-support

commit_message:
Disable keystone client if running under Py3K

Since keystoneclient is not Py3K compliant, it should be disabled when
running under python >= 2.7

Partially-implements: py3k-support
Change-Id: I9016748b3fc65f1437cb0d561b738ede704f642f

commit_message:
Remove gettext magic and import _ explicitly

Instead of magically loading `_` into python built-in globals, import it
explicitly where needed.

Partially-implements: py3k-support
Change-Id: Icfedf9f86ead81bbee038506a91c456907af0d05

commit_message:
Install guide: recommend 64-bit OS

Add some text to the install guide to recommend installing a 64-bit
operating system. Also links to Ops Guide for system requirements.

Motivated by this comment in the docs:
http://docs.openstack.org/havana/install-guide/install/apt/content/nova-boot.html#comment-1146233396

Change-Id: Iabe612024be0f6fcf335cf2daaf3ea77bed3cd86
backport: havana

commit_message:
Added error logging for http store

http store logs an error message when the remote location
fails to return the image, returns invalid status or
if it exceeds maximum redirects

Change-Id: I43c74395bc4632a97761ae4c11474bfeb823c85a
Closes-Bug: #1257234

Without a unique name, the scheduler (and anything else, really) will
consider each of these nova-compute processes as being one and the same,

commit_message:
Assign unique name to each fake nova-compute

Without a unique name, the scheduler (and anything else, really) will
consider each of these nova-compute processes as being one and the same,
so only one entry in the services table, only one hypervisor seen by the
scheduler, etc. Assigning unique names lets us simulate an arbitrary
amount of nova-computes which is very handy for benchmarking the
scheduler.

Change-Id: Ie03aad81bd2a8e73b876a9eae934bc00bf2f71e9

Bug #1257888: Remote Designate Agent Call Fails

Fix the Agent RPC API method signatures to align properly with the method signatures of the backend methods.

commit_message:
Fix a couple of INI whitespace bugs

* iniset() bails if no section or option (attribute) is supplied
* merge_config_file() properly skips lines with only whitespace

* Also split the ini-tests into their own script

Bug 1257954

Change-Id: Ie31c5bd0df8dfed129fbcf1e37228aaf25e9305d

commit_message:
Update tox.ini to use new features

Reasons:
 - tox update v1.6
Changes:
 - tox 1.6 allows us to skip the sdist step, which is slow.
 - It also allows us to override the install line. In this case, it's
   important as it allows us to stop getting pre-release software we
   weren't asking for.

Original patch by Monty Taylor, talked about here:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/015495.html

Change-Id: Ief0a44a8d982a12ff5158c1223487d27b75b950e

commit_message:
Updates tox.ini to use new features

Reasons:
 - tox update v1.6

Changes:
 - tox 1.6 allows us to skip the sdist step, which is slow.
 - It also allows us to override the install line. In this case, it's
   important as it allows us to stop getting pre-release software we
   weren't asking for.

Original patch by Monty Taylor, talked about here:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/015495.html

Change-Id: I3d857f8ef19b49e0a09b50a9eda7121b28329532

commit_message:
Add Cinder backend to image store

Cinder is an potiential backend in Glance.
This patchs aims to:
- create glance::backend::cinder
- improve spec_helper using shared_examples

Change-Id: I15e5de8281ff2e60465fedda97d9c9ccf808386c
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit eb7c33bb1f04acde5e55cfee37fa900af0f3bf5f)

commit_message:
Add Ceph as backup backend support

Cinder backup could use Ceph as backend.
This patch aims to create cinder::backup::ceph class to use this driver.

Change-Id: Ib82b94f3e2d5d9e2287a570a435d469656c9a756
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit c00c752994584600465e36cdf96f547fbe9696e5)

commit_message:
Improve Cinder Backup support

In my last commit on Cinder module, I add cinder::backup::swift
without adding cinder::backup class which is useful to ensure that
package is installed and service is running.
It also includes variables related to backup configuration.

Note: swift is one of the drivers of backup in Cinder, other ones should
be included in manifests/backup/<driver>.pp

Change-Id: I1a55245abe61f9bbd71568d76ed00e0ecf08307e
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5da2beb74d7dc73b4f050f5fb474c473688d206f)

commit_message:
Fix UnboundLocalError in libvirt.driver._close_callback

If for whatever reason _wrapped_conn is None or not equal to the conn
parameter passed to the _close_callback method, the local _error
variable won't be set when calling set_host_enabled and result in an
UnboundLocalError.

Partial-Bug: #1257644

Change-Id: I40855f22d5449f3b3646c90fe2d9a71560eb86c4

commit_message:
Add Swift as backup backend support

Cinder can backup volumes in different backends.
Swift will be the first one supported by puppet-cinder.

New class: cinder::backup::swift

Change-Id: Iec0a48681da8fd987955cabae49d411ede1e255e
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit f0b2f7daa7205b3f709063fded713a4cb6b7d0db)

commit_message:
Add Glance support

Glance support in Cinder is used to convert images into volumes
or send volumes into Glance with the goal to boot virtual machines
from volumes.

Change-Id: Ie2c9ed382254e374d12242edc7d57077fbbcd240
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5d91bf3210a9b25d724fc21068e22c9d322c27a5)

commit_message:
Add import for publisher_rpc option

If this option is not imported a NoSuchOptError is
raised starting the ceilometer-collector service

Closes-Bug: #1258650
Change-Id: I46f8a0510603d31ce8cc9a0b5b15880083138487

commit_message:
Use select-mirror in devstack-gate

The select-mirror logic has grown more complex, but devstack-gate's
mirror selection has not kept up. Instead of duplicating, just reuse the
existing script.

This change depends on:

  https://review.openstack.org/59196
  https://review.openstack.org/58153

Change-Id: Icbc240b83961834083f6044b30abb7f1d7321306

commit_message:
Move create network section to the bottom

Locate Create the base Neutron networks section after the sections
involving installation of Neutron on the network, controller, and
compute nodes, which makes the order more sense.

backport: havana

(cherry picked from commit d0ce7524fd19993659b88df84b5ebcab46f65a52)

commit_message:
Add Ironic to setup-clienttools

Ironic has pushed its first client release to Pypi. This patch adds
Ironic to the client tools installed by setup-clienttools. This will
integrate Ironic more closely with the TripleO story and allow Ironic
Dev's to follow the devtest script with less deviation.

Also add scripts/ironic to .gitignore file.

Change-Id: Ib384c31a9b5c328f58040da77f507cc84b055be4

commit_message:
Don't forget to return self

To retain the functionality where we can chain
function calls to add, link we need to return the
object we are acting on (instead of none).

Change-Id: Iadf0f9d3a21b6d079c1edd29063196180f5222ed

commit_message:
Formalize deprecation of token_api.list_tokens

The token_api.list_tokens method should really only be used internally
to keystone.  This has been the case (as per the docstring) since the
Havana development cycle.  This patchset formalizes the deprecation and
slates the public access to token_api.list_tokens to be removed once
Icehouse ships.

bp: deprecated-as-of-icehouse
Change-Id: I30a066d3775e67fd4a84f07dc351fcfd62751045

commit_message:
Refactor StorageQuotaFull test cases in test_quota

There were two test cases in test_quota that shared the same name, but
did almost the same thing. After a bit of digging, it looked like most
of the test cases did the almost same thing, so I refactored the common
bits and fixed the test case name duplication.

Partial-Bug: #1259036
Change-Id: I828eea570d358d98520c7201454c03ba174a35ad

commit_message:
Add tools/conf/check_uptodate to tox.ini

To ensure that our sample config file, etc/ironic/ironic.conf.sample,
does not get out of sync with the code, this patch introduces a check
to tox that will compare the proposed ironic.conf.sample to a
freshly generated one, and error if they are not identical.

Ported from Nova's tools/config/check_uptodate.sh script.

Change-Id: Ic2898142754547e32bc4c03d23eca5d6a33721fc
Closes-bug: 1255621

commit_message:
Remove TestRegistryDB dependency on TestRegistryAPI

TestRegistryDB does not set up the sqlalchemy db it uses with the db models.
These tests only pass when run in conjunction with TestRegistryAPI because that
test case does set up the db. TestRegistryDB should set up the DB as it needs
to.

Fixes bug 1247629

Change-Id: Ib0629634e567e1fb9b98dac50025f5309cd4efec

commit_message:
RBD add() now returns correct size if given zero

If the RBD store add() is provided with image_size of zero, it
will calculate based on data provided and return the new size.

Change-Id: I06375bcfef7808905b466432e5ca100c942297eb
Closes-bug: 1256044

[{'created': '2013-11-22 10:57:22.000000000', 'message': "Process image BDM earlier to avoid duplicates

If the block device mapping from the image properties are not handled at
the same time as the ones defined from the API, we might make the false
assumption that the instance has no root and failing or, in the case
we're booting from an image that only defines a BDM and has no disk,
creating a local disk BDM as root and ending up with two root devices
which is forbidden.

This patch moves the handling of the image block device mappings to the
same method were we check the ones provided throught the API. This
allows nova to decide wether the instance needs a local disk from an
image if no root device is defined in any of the block device mappings.

Change-Id: Ide95357895ab4dd1338ab5ee3ec25294af1d010b
Closes-Bug: #1246327
(cherry picked from commit 482dfeb113f1e0ff814aa1fc980d67e0c8b06d76)
"}]
commit_message:
Process image BDM earlier to avoid duplicates

If the block device mapping from the image properties are not handled at
the same time as the ones defined from the API, we might make the false
assumption that the instance has no root and failing or, in the case
we're booting from an image that only defines a BDM and has no disk,
creating a local disk BDM as root and ending up with two root devices
which is forbidden.

This patch moves the handling of the image block device mappings to the
same method were we check the ones provided throught the API. This
allows nova to decide wether the instance needs a local disk from an
image if no root device is defined in any of the block device mappings.

Change-Id: Ide95357895ab4dd1338ab5ee3ec25294af1d010b
Closes-Bug: #1246327
(cherry picked from commit 482dfeb113f1e0ff814aa1fc980d67e0c8b06d76)

[{'created': '2013-12-08 05:00:18.000000000', 'message': 'Unify different names between Python2/3 with six.moves

Some modules use different names in Python2 and Python3. Use six.moves
to make them work well in Python2 and Python3.
This is changes mapping:

six.moves                Python 2             Python 3
filter                   itertools.ifilter()  filter()
urllib.parse.quote()     urllib.quote()       urllib.parse.quote()
urllib.parse.urlparse()  urlparse.urlparse()  urllib.parse.urlparse()

Change-Id: Ia27ebf6057d91d0e129fbe90f995cfdaa89efa8a
'}, {'created': '2013-12-09 10:20:40.000000000', 'message': 'Unify different names between Python2 and Python3

Some modules have different names in Python2 and Python3. This patch
make them compatible with Python 3.

 * Use six.moves.filter instead of itertools.ifilter() in Python 2.
 * Use common.py3kcompat.urlutils instead of urllib and urlparse.

Change-Id: Ia27ebf6057d91d0e129fbe90f995cfdaa89efa8a
'}]
commit_message:
Unify different names between Python2 and Python3

Some modules have different names in Python2 and Python3. This patch
make them compatible with Python 3.

 * Use six.moves.filter instead of itertools.ifilter() in Python 2.
 * Use common.py3kcompat.urlutils instead of urllib and urlparse.

Change-Id: Ia27ebf6057d91d0e129fbe90f995cfdaa89efa8a

commit_message:
Replace data structures' attribute with six module

In Python 3, some data structures' attribute is different in Python 2.
See http://pythonhosted.org/six/#object-model-compatibility
This is change mapping:

   six               Python 2           Python 3
six.next(it)         it.next()          next(it)
six.iterkeys(dict)   dict.iterkeys()    dict.keys()
six.itervalues(dict) dict.itervalues()  dict.values()

Implements: blueprint make-python3-compatible
Change-Id: Ida48f39ff230860feee7305b93b134c625a21663

commit_message:
Brick LVM: Set C locale when gathering PV info

Some locales use commas as decimal separators, which means
that code breaks when someone expects to be able to use the
PV size as a float.

Change-Id: Idceb405e021ea8a0f44e19be43bad1307fbbb51c
Related-Bug: 1219963

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-14 19:03:56.000000000', 'message': 'Protect create from vol/snap from delete

This patch adds a lockfile between create volume from volume or
snapshot and delete volume/snapshot operations in order to avoid
the scenario where one of these operations is executed while the
other is still in progress.

Change-Id: Ie4bc0af789ab232593f55aa2f6b34345eb9b9929
Fixes: bug 1251334
'}, {'created': '2013-11-20 15:49:54.000000000', 'message': 'Adds lock for create from vol/snap to avoid race conditions

This patch protects create from volume/snapshot by using a
lockfile to protect the operation from concurrent deletes of
the volume/snapshot used in the create operation.

Currently, if a volume/snapshot is deleted while a volume is
being created from it that delete may complete during the
create operation thus leaving the new volume in error or stuck
state. This lock will ensure that:

commit_message:
Adds lock for create from vol/snap to avoid race conditions

This patch protects create from volume/snapshot by using a
lockfile to protect the operation from concurrent deletes of
the volume/snapshot used in the create operation.

Currently, if a volume/snapshot is deleted while a volume is
being created from it that delete may complete during the
create operation thus leaving the new volume in error or stuck
state. This lock will ensure that:

(a) if a create of VolA from snap/volB is in progress, any
    delete requests for snap/volB will wait until the create
    is complete.

(b) if a delete of snap/volA is in progress, any create from
    snap/volA will wait until snap/volA delete is complete.

Co-authored-by: Takashi Natsume <natsume.takashi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Closes-Bug: 1251334
Change-Id: Ie4bc0af789ab232593f55aa2f6b34345eb9b9929

commit_message:
xenapi: stop hang during glance download

It seems there are cases when the server gets stuck in a building state
because the download from glance fails, but the nova-compute doesn't
find out.

After some code inspect, a likely cause seems to related to having no
socket timeout inside urllib2 when we download the image from glance. A
workaround for this issue is to configure the default socket timeout as
described here:
http://docs.python.org/3.1/howto/urllib2.html#sockets-and-layers

Fixes bug 1251650
Change-Id: I8b34d95d3524f3825b28e61cbbb59290653d3711

Seems like the code new code is attempting to catch exceptions thrown by LOG.exception and falling back to logging to syslog. Previously, if LOG.exception threw an exception, no attempt to log to syslog occurred and the error could silently fail. Although not a likely event, this case could occur if disk became full or some other logging error failed.'}, {'account_id': 100, 'date': '2012-10-09 16:02:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The logging module handles exceptions itself (and logs *those* exceptions) and won't propagate them up the callstack:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/21536/

If the call to unicode() fails, then that should get logged already as is. So I'm still not seeing how this patch can help. Especially since the given example works fine for me."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2012-10-17 06:03:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Failsafe wsgi logging

In the event of wsgi logging failure, write the traceback
to the syslog.

Fixes Bug: 1054501
Change-Id: I5da8094e767cd8662513fe11719495c39ecc29b4

commit_message:
Add IgnoreAttemptedHostsFilter to oslo

IgnoreAttemptedHostsFilter is RetryFilter that is using in nova and
cinder, so we can put it to oslo and then back port it to both nova
and cinder.

Change-Id: Ia355810b106fee14a55f48081301a310979befac
Implements part of bp oslo-more-filters

Change-Id: Iad5d3e47c8235eadd52a8193657aebb92158568b

Previously, ThreadGroup.wait and ThreadGroup.stop would iterate over
the self.threads list and call the wait or stop method on each one.
This list could potentially be edited concurrently by the _thread_done
callbacks and remove some items in the list.  As a result, the wait

commit_message:
Make wait & stop methods work on all threads

Previously, ThreadGroup.wait and ThreadGroup.stop would iterate over
the self.threads list and call the wait or stop method on each one.
This list could potentially be edited concurrently by the _thread_done
callbacks and remove some items in the list.  As a result, the wait
method would not actually wait for all threads in the thread group.

Change-Id: Iad5d3e47c8235eadd52a8193657aebb92158568b
Closes-Bug: #1196525

commit_message:
Updates tox.ini to use new features

Reasons:
 - tox update v1.6

Changes:
 - tox 1.6 allows us to skip the sdist step, which is slow.
 - It also allows us to override the install line. In this case, it's
   important as it allows us to stop getting pre-release software we
   weren't asking for.

Original patch by Monty Taylor, talked about here:
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/015495.html

Rushi, thanks for reviewing. This change does not depend on any other submission, it is instead a fix for the same bug 1249782.

The change from Jon Bernard fixes the thin pool free space reporting by returning "infinte" free space regardless of the actual consumption, basing on the idea that by doing so we leverage the lvm overcommit facility.

This change instead returns the actual free space available in the thin pool, basing on the idea that we will still have "transparent" overcommit from lvm but also track real data usage about the physical space consumption, useful to, for instance, the scheduler.

Please get in touch with Jon and John to see which one of the two fits better.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-12-04 11:30:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

NOTE: this change does not report about the virual space usage of volumes, which would impede overcommit, but about the actual physical space usage and, as such, doesn't prevent errors due to volumes growing past the thin pool"}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2013-12-04 18:07:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Returns thin pool free space calculated from actual usage

This change adds a hidden method which calculates the thin
pool free space from the data_percent LVM options and reports it
accordingly in _update_volume_stats()

Change-Id: Id6a69644505ca10811db458ea90ed10f643054b2
Closes-Bug: 1249782

commit_message:
Setup user and endpoints for Savanna

* create savanna user with admin role for auth token checks
* create service data_processing
* create savanna endpoint
* use savanna user for auth token checks

It's needed for running tempest tests.

Change-Id: Iff26960746e36012c275f43c0de0dedcaebc8b0a

commit_message:
Add missing vpnaas class in example manifest

examples/neutron was missing neutron::agents::vpnaas which is useful
for people wanting to write manifests based on puppet-neutron module.

Change-Id: I374c4315472d46397c1cc2152bd35e1cdfd7336a
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit 37d1c5b81087d241a26a6ee84278fb0b9bf1eabe)

commit_message:
Updates to params.pp for mongo and postgres packages

*) Removed the hardcoded postgres package from db.pp
*) Changed the mongo package to python-pymongo for RHEL

Change-Id: Ib975f9ce03ee8ffa423e75b62b595bcdefdd1eed
Signed-off-by: Francesco Vollero <fvollero@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 0fb3b8f693ba4cc24bdcfb1f61de843343a13e75)

commit_message:
Alarm: record history support

Ceilometer Alarm is able to record alarm change events.
This patch add this support in manifest.

Change-Id: Id8ece03dfd3491cd2886a345771df9622d702190
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
(cherry picked from commit 24a712516bb721bd62ead06cabadc631b8b7f060)

changed rabbit_virtualhost(wrong) to rabbit_virtual_host

the puppet module configures a rabbit_virtualhost, there is a missing underscore (rabbit_virtual_host). changed this for manifest and tests.

Change-Id: I02b34eb6531cfa0071a7e52f5a97f0e952f8ea85

commit_message:
CSV Summary not working inside Admin panel.

When browsing Project usages from 'Admin->Projects->More->View Usages'
an AttributeError exception is thrown due to missing csv_render_class
attribute.
Also, project_id instead of tenant_id in BaseUsage  were expected, so
any request to /admin/projects/[id]/usage/ will always return the current
tenant from session.
This fix reuse logic from project/overview/ into this view.

Change-Id: I7d762569a7de176fdb8545a226e563afac34adae
Closes-Bug: #1255667

commit_message:
Fix provisioning progress calculation

* don't send ready status in provision handler
  because nodes are not provisioned yet in
  this handler
* fix undefined variable in provision handler
* fix nodes calculations statuses in
  watch_provision_progress method. Firstly get
  all nodes in error status, then retrieve nodes
  which ready and add their status to result
  variable.
* fix typo in logs

Closes-bug: #1257342
Closes-bug: #1249994
Change-Id: I56e06ade671795fc8c87b7e84e159df7abdba34b

commit_message:
Fix progress bar calculation when provisioning is running

Separated deployment and provisioning progress bar
calculation because orchestrator now sends progress
for provisioning task, not for deployment task
as it was before.

Closes-bug: #1257342
Change-Id: Ie0c84ee92ec6f027b483e6f9116755f21489ec8d

Hmm, so this is sorting on first name ? email ? Why is that more relevant than sorting on deprecation date ?'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-27 21:11:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

It's easy to sort that way as we add new ones ? :)"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-11-28 08:54:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

@lifeless: since all extra-ATCs get rights for one year, it's actually simpler to just add them to the end of the list.

The only two actions we (I) do with this list is adding new people (currently: add at bottom of list) and removing deprecated people (currently: look at top of list). Sorting the list alphabetically arguably makes both those tasks more difficult. And I'm unclear what it gives us in exchange."}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2013-12-02 20:10:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Meh, I don't really have an opinion here."}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2013-12-09 15:10:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned

sorting by date seems to be the general preference... so, done!'}]

commit_message:
Generic benchmark cleanup

Provides implementation for generic benchmark cleanup which is run with
the same concurrency as specified in the benchmark's configuration. The
cleanup logic encompasses the common resources which would be created
via benchmarks such as servers, images, volumes, etc.

Implements: blueprint benchmark-cloud-cleanup

Change-Id: I9e9a66795823c68486aa33d79d312373d825fe43

I am confused by a number of things: 1) the default is the same for both ovs_neutron_plugin.ini and nova.conf; 2) AFAIK, when using the vcdriver and neutron, you don't need to run the l2 agent; 3) a bug for neutron was filed, but a fix for the documentation was targeted, so which one is it? As a matter of fact, when it comes to networking there are multiple deployment options that can be chosen of which I see no clear documentation, so this patch may turn out to be more elaborated than it started to be.

So in a nutshell, I suggest this change be abandoned in favor for one that aims at clarifying the integration between nova and neutron when the hypervisor of choice is vmware."}, {'account_id': 7823, 'date': '2013-12-01 15:15:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Armando for your valued comments, something I need to clarify:
1) the default is the same for both ovs_neutron_plugin.ini and nova.conf;
yes, from the code, I think all default values for the integration bridge are named as "br-int", where vm instance interface will be pluged in vmware ESXI host.
2) AFAIK, when using the vcdriver and neutron, you don't need to run the l2 agent;
Yes, that's true, but I happen to start neutron l2 agent that time, then found out that if I want to change the integration bridge where vm located on vcenter,  "neutron_ovs_bridge" should be configured other than "vmware.integration_bridge" , that's why I think this document should be correct the description,
also I will delete the line 
/"etc/neutron/plugins/openvswitch/ovs_neutron_plugin.ini" in
next patch, sorry for this mistake.
3) a bug for neutron was filed, but a fix for the documentation was targeted, so which one is it?
Suddenly I realized that this is not a neutron bug, I will drop the bug pointed, sorry for that too. >_<'}, {'account_id': 7823, 'date': '2013-12-02 05:47:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-02 05:52:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Correct the port group defined location in vmware guide

The right port group defined location is section [DEFAULT]
"neutron_ovs_bridge=" in file nova.conf, if using vcenter
driver with OpenStack Networking Service and OVS agent.

Change-Id: I9430afa843cc44694b7aca11793ec0fb640b49c6

Cleaned up Training Guide Module 001 - Brief Overview

commit_message:
Install guide: don't duplicate AMQP configuration

The nova-network section redefines the rabbit_host option. This doesn't
hurt but might lead to problems if the user wants to change the settings
later.

Change-Id: I71481813c77dfa40ca664e99afe7885141b6361f
backport: havana

commit_message:
xenapi: display IP and DevStack result on console

The devstack setup service can update /etc/issue, displaying the status
of the installation and the VM's management IP. With this change, after
the devstack service finsihed, the login prompt will look like this:

OpenStack VM - Installed by DevStack
  Management IP:   10.219.3.108
  Devstack run:    SUCCEEDED

DevStackOSDomU login:

This helps people to log in to their system.

Change-Id: Idd6bbd5faf9ced5618cd3e95191bfc3b89473fa2

commit_message:
Refactoring for generic benchmark cleanup

Initial refactoring which will be used in the generic benchmark cleanup
implementation. Specifically the utility functions which existed in the
NovaScenarios class are now exposed in benchmark.test_utils. Moreover a
few of these functions have been enahanced to be more generic/flexible
in nature.

Subsequent patch will provide the actual generic cleanup.

Implements partial: blueprint benchmark-cloud-cleanup

Change-Id: I7e25dd006e46bf66fd9419090ea310629ba7d19f

commit_message:
Add LeastRouters Scheduler to Neutron L3 Agent

Allow scheduling of a virtual router on an L3 Agent node with the least
number of routers currently scheduled. This scheduler can be used
instead of the default random scheduler.

Also refactor the l3_agent_scheduler to allow for adding new schedulers.

Implement blueprint lessrouter-scheduler
Change-Id: Ie539c08bdc8a6e1430a106f77d08f15abd0903e7

commit_message:
Remove Network and Vlan models

These models are removed and NetworkGroup model have all relationships that Network model had.
Vlan model was utilized to check that newly created networks
have the same VLAN IDs being assigned as networks of other clusters.
Now this can be checked using NetworkGroup model but not checked
because the result of this checking was used for logging only.

Implements: blueprint nailgun-remove-network-model

Change-Id: Iaec7d5acdb0e47d9e9cf4c224e1be768df83107f

commit_message:
Add mpcut.sh for milestone-proposed branch cutting

Add an mpcut.sh script (similar to the mpdelivery.sh script) which
handles all steps required at milestone-proposed branch cutting
time in the release process:

- Creating milestone-proposed branch in gerrit
- Wait for tarball creation (calls wait_for_tarball.py)
- Set all FixCommitted bugs to FixReleased (calls process_bugs.py)

Additionally add a .gitreview for convenient git-review usage.

Change-Id: Ia535119bd47ce49edc155819ca4c68be6aa0efe9

commit_message:
Removes Unneeded mysql::server Dependency

Previously, the heat::db::mysql class contained a dependency on
mysql::server. This dependency is unneeded since mysql::db requires
mysql::config, which depends on mysql::server. Additionally, the
mysql::server dependency causes MYSQL HA installations such as
Galera to fail. Lastly, this aligns the class more closely with
the other [OPENSTACK_SERVICE]::db::mysql classes.

Change-Id: Ie6c4d3c8aaa531502bc5b9cd66a547f1f506385f
(cherry picked from commit 65766e8deea9a9a45c24d637f33a0fb6539415c9)

commit_message:
Documentation update: grunt-cli is needed for fuel ISO build

requirejs is not needed anymore, it is installed locally on ISO build
nodejs should be installed from PPA since default version is too old

Closes-Bug: 1258503

Change-Id: I7f648b8991f30a3f31888a3c0d5dd386d859ca3a

commit_message:
l3_agent: make process_router more robust

If internal_network_added/removed fails, _sync_routers_task will call
process_router to do fault recovery. Because the port is already
added/removed to/from ri.internal_ports, internal_network_added or
internal_network_removed will not be called again.

The patch fix this issue by calling ri.internal_ports.append/removed
only if internal_network_added/removed succeed. Without the patch,
the added testcases would fail.

Change-Id: I2d2e004caa670c1624257c1d7ccc900438b42d08
Co-Authored-By: Hirofumi Ichihara <ichihara.hirofumi@lab.ntt.co.jp>
Closes-Bug: #1255871

commit_message:
Create memcache_servers option

Permits use of one or more memcache servers for token storage.
Use to override default server (localhost:11211) when token_driver
is keystone.token.backends.memcache.Token.

Change-Id: Iaeb0c896d4907fd520db9b60e3af002b3711bc75
(cherry picked from commit 364ddff9ea6fcb20797936dff87d039bf85de607)

commit_message:
Remove dead code _arp_spoofing_rule()

This code should have been removed when the allowed_address_pair
extension was added here (0efce6195fa7be80e110bd841dc9b3537a94c376).
The arp spoofing rules are handled in the method _setup_spoof_filter_chain().

Reported by: Amir Sadoughi that this was crud I left behind :)

Change-Id: Ib0e2e2a5c13fb8fa7af1f988510143f40ac335e2
Closes-bug: #1258629

commit_message:
Import translations for Havana 2013.2.1 udpate

* Import the latest translations of ~100% completed languages.
  12 translated languages are avaialable.
* Update POT files

This commit is directly proposed to stable/havana branch because
strings are different between stable/havana and master branches.

Change-Id: I8e81552d868eab8ad078db3a0cb2a912bd050066
Closes-Bug: #1258462

commit_message:
Broken charting for non compute resources

- Code for resource charts contained query that
  filtered only nova instances. That condition
  is removed. Now it filters resources by the
  meter name.

Fixes bug 1243796

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tests.py

Change-Id: I7debb2b457ede83b726934c082f22307ddc0c630
(cherry picked from commit 1e1da618bb75783e1d8316894705c01f7bb9153b)

commit_message:
Remove a task from providers

The patch removes a task from server providers. An initialization method
was added to a base class of server providers. The method takes a two
position arguments: a deployment and a configuration. The class method
get_provider was also changed and has got a similar interface.

All present providers were adapted to the new interface.

blueprint independent-deploy

Change-Id: I1f56b7ce1903d3f51713228df0a4a90ccdb199ca

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-28 15:49:13.000000000', 'message': "Remove duplicate setting of os_type in libvirt config builder

In the following change

  commit 158d821204d2f79cc06c1443562b3ce9bbe7cb9f
  Author: Christoph Thiel <cthiel@suse.com>
  Date:   Thu Jul 26 00:07:24 2012 +0200

    libvirt driver: set os_type to support xen hvm/pv

The libvirt driver get_guest_config() method was changed to
use the 'vm_mode' property from the instance to set the guest
os_type attribute. If this property was not set, then it used
defaults based on the virt type. Unfortunately it neglected to
remove most of the existing later code which also set os_type
based on virt type. So in many cases we end up setting the
os_type twice. Fortunately this did not have any ill effects,
since only Xen currently needs the ability to override os_type
using 'vm_mode'. This change cleans up the mess to avoid
future confusion & problems.

Change-Id: Ib11cb1196755f993b07e892e9f2adfc36e44a4e2
Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrange <berrange@redhat.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Remove duplicate setting of os_type in libvirt config builder

In the following change

  commit 158d821204d2f79cc06c1443562b3ce9bbe7cb9f
  Author: Christoph Thiel <cthiel@suse.com>
  Date:   Thu Jul 26 00:07:24 2012 +0200

    libvirt driver: set os_type to support xen hvm/pv

The libvirt driver get_guest_config() method was changed to
use the 'vm_mode' property from the instance to set the guest
os_type attribute. If this property was not set, then it used
defaults based on the virt type. Unfortunately it neglected to
remove most of the existing later code which also set os_type
based on virt type. So in many cases we end up setting the
os_type twice. Fortunately this did not have any ill effects,
since only Xen currently needs the ability to override os_type
using 'vm_mode'. This change cleans up the mess to avoid
future confusion & problems.

Change-Id: Ib11cb1196755f993b07e892e9f2adfc36e44a4e2
Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrange <berrange@redhat.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-28 15:49:12.000000000', 'message': "Fix logic in LibvirtConnTestCase._check_xml_and_uri

The _check_xml_and_uri method has two loops making it
iterate over different hypervisor types. By default it
will iterate over qemu, kvm, xen and lxc, but it can be
made to only check xen by setting the 'xen_only' param
or the 'expect_xen_hvm' parameters.

Unfortunately the second loop is only filtered if the
'expect_xen_hvm' parameter is set, not if only the
'xen_only' parameter is set. This flaw hasn't showed
up before, due to a flaw elsewhere in the libvirt
driver code, cancelling it out.

Change-Id: If70faa05975b726067ab6edaa505ca8d0c230a38
Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrange <berrange@redhat.com>
"}]
commit_message:
Fix logic in LibvirtConnTestCase._check_xml_and_uri

The _check_xml_and_uri method has two loops making it
iterate over different hypervisor types. By default it
will iterate over qemu, kvm, xen and lxc, but it can be
made to only check xen by setting the 'xen_only' param
or the 'expect_xen_hvm' parameters.

Unfortunately the second loop is only filtered if the
'expect_xen_hvm' parameter is set, not if only the
'xen_only' parameter is set. This flaw hasn't showed
up before, due to a flaw elsewhere in the libvirt
driver code, cancelling it out.

Change-Id: If70faa05975b726067ab6edaa505ca8d0c230a38
Signed-off-by: Daniel P. Berrange <berrange@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix test_tpool_execute_calls_libvirt against fakelibvirt

Change aded4a72b70d936df2771d1a6d35dd71e356de71 added default
values to the Connection class in fakelibvirt, but the default
URI value of None is only accepted if a global in fakelibvrit,
allow_default_uri_connection, is true.  This seems to be a
feature to support test_fakelibvirt

test_tpool_execute_calls_libvirt in test_libvirt.py uses the
default values for Connection but sometimes fails in a full
test run, presumably because the hidden global in fakelibvirt
is left in the wrong state.  This change passes in a URI
to avoid that issue.

Closes-Bug:  #1258603

Change-Id: Idd09e3b7c710e562599a1537d112cd29d2386ade

commit_message:
Remove legacy sqlalchemy-migrate engine patching

We don't need to patch the engine instance to be used by
sqlalchemy-migrate since its 0.8.2 version was released
and we started to depend on it in global-requirements
(Icde6248ca102884323d7912bab0f4a716aa294ec).

Similar change to Nova: I5f80dfc07f8256716d025002fc1a1f47e58b2142

Change-Id: I6fe7a2f396c4445e7a00031780c1804a865d1ab8

commit_message:
Use six.moves.queue instead of Queue

The Queue module has been renamed to queue in Python 3.
Use six.moves.queue to fit the change.

http://docs.python.org/2/library/queue.html#module-Queue

Change-Id: I2940f34d161b2e3cbc5464619f76e6adea4ef9f6

commit_message:
Clean up some duplicated code in mem_diskfile.DiskFile

We recently had an issue with some Swift logic in the base DiskFile that
resulted in the introduction of the new DiskFileExpired exception.

The mem_diskfile implementation didn't get updated so the bug remained there.

This change begins the work of moving the mem_diskfile implementaiton to
subclass(es) of the base diskfile implementation.  Because the
mem_diskfile.DiskFile no longer duplicates the X-Delete-At logic in
_verify_integrity the new behavior for DiskFileException is inherited.

The async_update work is an attempt to pre-empt a similar problem in
subclasses reimplementing ObjectController.async_update.  This change does not
remove the duplication of DiskFileReader.app_iter_range and .app_iter_ranges.

Change-Id: Ic3951d2eac3e4c5ff122ff4faa0e35ad2b6008b2

This code is fine. But I wonder if we are taking the right approach. Does each event actually need a uuid?

Why don't we just use stack_id + offset? As in, we could just have each event list start at 0, and go up from there?

That would allow us to have ordering by the event offset, and it would keep the table smaller. It would also avoid a call to the CPU intensive uuid4 function.

I can't think of a time where we want to address an event without its' stack.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 9275, 'date': '2013-12-05 23:58:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

(1 inline comment)

'}, {'account_id': 9331, 'date': '2013-12-06 15:51:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Clint:
I got your point, but...
1) If we use any kind of offset starting with 0, we need a way to know which the next value will be, and the only option I imagine is to persist that offset in the database (separately or using the last record to know the next value), and that could be more expensive than the uuid4 generation.
2) If we use stack_id + offset, the table will be larger than with the uuid option alone, because the stack_id is a uuid.
3) If we need to sort the events, we can use the created_at/updated_at column.
I'm open to any counterproposal or thoughts about this, though!

Cheers."}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-12-06 19:12:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

> 1) If we use any kind of offset starting with 0, we need a way to know which the next value will be, and the only option I imagine is to persist that offset in the database (separately or using the last record to know the next value), and that could be more expensive than the uuid4 generation.

The transaction needed might be beyond sqlalchemy, but it would not be expensive at all:

begin;@offset=''; select @offset := max(offset) from events where stack_id='xxxxxxxxxxxx';@offset := @offset + 1;insert ..;commit

The select is a single read from the first record of the primary key which is crazy fast in InnoDB as you can seek directly to the logical block containing the row. Probably fast in pgsql as well.

But I acknowledge this makes it more complex and would make event storage in a nosql database complicated.

> 2) If we use stack_id + offset, the table will be larger than with the uuid option alone, because the stack_id is a uuid.

stack_id is already in the table, but for some reason I had thought it was also already indexed. It isn't, so in that case I was dead wrong about the index size.

> 3) If we need to sort the events, we can use the created_at/updated_at column.
> I'm open to any counterproposal or thoughts about this, though!
> 

created_at is used now and events are often out of order because this is a single-second resolution. Perhaps we can make it sub-second and solve the sorting problem, as I think the order of events is actually _critical_ when debugging.

Anyway, thanks for responding. I'm convinced, UUID is simpler so +2"}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-12-09 07:24:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Change ID column of Event table to UUID

If you are using a public Heat you can use the event ID in
'heat event-list' to measure how much activity the service provider
has in their heat installation.

To avoid this, the Id column of the Event table was changed from
autoincremental integer to a uuid.

Added some unit tests in order to ensure that events with integer or
uuid id pass through the API, since we have a migration which will
leave behind integer ids.

Change-Id: Ib3eddb700738cb3667c72977a9a5011209acd6d7
Closes-Bug: #1249159

commit_message:
refactor test_catalog

- Tests for "missing" attributes are actually testing with null values,
  not missing keys.
- Not being able to explicitly provide alternative URLs resulting in
  hacky workarounds that can be avoiding by simply exposing kwargs with
  reasonable defaults
- Several tests redundantly asserted the expected response status, which
  is already handled by the test framework

Change-Id: Icadb4927bcf03ca7e79fef1507e419a4932f32a9
Related-Bug: 1250765

commit_message:
Fixes case insensitive for resp body

Create metadata for a volume with key-value set, which key in uppercase
and lowercase(e.g.{"key": "v1", "KEY": "V1"), the server accept the
request and return the key-value set {"key": "v1", "KEY": "V1"}. But the
server just add one metadata because the server is not case sensitive.

The patch will modify the resp body with the one which the server added.

update_all has the same ploblem.

Fixes errors on v2 unittest without difficulty.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1258004

Change-Id: Ic337c0a351ac234493e1d73b86ba87520f32289a

commit_message:
Convert lvm_mirrors to int

When the location_info is parsed and `lvm_mirrors` extracted, it is not
being converted to int. This causes some boolean checks to return True
even when there are not mirrors enabled because of the u'0'.

Closes-bug: #1258133
Change-Id: I67c463d9f139fe326bbcab4d193c45459129b514

commit_message:
Create Auth Plugin out of HTTPClient

To support current behaviour we take the current code from the base
client and turn it into a plugin. The appropriate plugin is specified by
the client and created on initialization.

We also add the get_token functions to the auth plugin class.

Change-Id: Ieefbd5f8aad76c0e1b91eee7579cf59dcba1baf1
Part of: blueprint auth-plugins

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp and *.swo
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: I976770f14c3ce699520f4867e2675ea53c074d19
Closes-Bug: #1255874

[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-25 09:52:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Build succeeded.

- gate-ironic-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/36/58236/1/check/gate-ironic-docs/230471a/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 4m 36s
- gate-ironic-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/36/58236/1/check/gate-ironic-pep8/d54a4ed : SUCCESS in 3m 14s
