- gate-ironic-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/36/58236/1/check/gate-ironic-python27/75a83a1 : SUCCESS in 2m 15s
'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-11-25 10:00:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

While I agree that H803 is a total waste of resource (-1 a patch just because a period)

Our commit message guideline is very clear about it, it says: "The first line should be limited to 50 characters and should not end with a period."[1]

So I think that it should be a general thing across openstack, not per project. Maybe we should start a threat on openstack-dev and see what people think about dropping it for all the openstack projects. So I'm -1 for now, because I would like the guideline to be changed for everybody before doing it per project.

~~~~~
[1]https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Summary_of_GIT_commit_message_structure'}, {'account_id': 6623, 'date': '2013-11-25 10:44:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Robert, if you're going to upload a new patch set, please consider adding more details to the commit message, e.g., an explanation why H803 is not needed."}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-11-25 10:56:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I agree with the patch, but this should be a general fix and not just a local one"}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:55:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

H803 is disabled in Cookiecutter, the reference project for new projects. It's also disabled in nova all tripleo projects, all infra projects etc. It's the one that says there must not be a . at the end of the first line of a commit message, which the list consensus was clearly that noone should review for-or-against this."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2013-11-25 17:56:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@ghe if you agree with it, why the -1? Removing it from Hacking is apparently contentious, but individual projects get to make their own decisions.'}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2013-11-25 18:20:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

@lifeless I agreed with the patch, but not about the place to be made... but you made my mind'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2013-11-26 10:04:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think there's no real right or wrong, some people prefer the first line to be limited to 72 instead of 50, some others wants to have the first letter to be capitalized enforced, etc, etc... It's a convention that at some point in time people agreed to follow, and at that time people choose to not end the first line with a period. The guideline[1] is very clear about that, and that's the guideline I point to people when their commit message is not well formatted, so if we change it in this project but not on openstack in general how can I point someone to a "partial" guideline? I can't.

I don't think that removing the period at the end of the first line is a hard limit on us, it's very simple and I vote to us to just adapt to what is default and keep things sane. If it's become a common sense across _all_ the projects and everyone agree in dropping that rule and remove it from the guideline then it's different and I will be fine with that decision.

So for now I still vote to keep things default and the most important to not create exceptions to the rules because the rule is simple to adapt to.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages#Summary_of_GIT_commit_message_structure'}, {'account_id': 6618, 'date': '2013-11-27 18:42:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Good grief. I shouldn't even need to look at this. I see Lucas' point of view but I'm a newcomer and there are a lot of hurdles. Maybe we should also make sure that all the comments we add in the code are grammatically correct and end with periods too. (Ignore that.) We should automate the commit message to strip out the period if we really don't want it."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2013-11-27 19:02:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Do not merge

I agree with Lucas' points, and would prefer to adhere to common policy where there is no *strong* reason to go against it. commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp and *.swo
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw[a-p]

Closes-Bug: #1255859

Change-Id: I22b6fa351dd565d4783f432c017c85706acd8397

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

Adding ignore for Eclipse IDE environment files
These files .project and .pydevproject should be
ignored while pushing to repositories.

Change-Id: I4f39372ae50d83c5d82e38dcaf3da3e2f4840701
Closes-Bug: #1256043

commit_message:
Instance call build_userdata directly

get_mime_string is only ever called once so caching the results
in self.mime_string is not necessary.

Change-Id: I36a1eb358b1228a946c5f8fa6e76869f10c398fd

commit_message:
Make build_userdata user_data_format aware

Over time different user_data_format values could assemble
different combinations of cloud-init parts.

As the default will remain user_data_format='HEAT_CFNTOOLS',
identical content will be generated for the Instance resource.

The Server resource now passes user_data_format, and no longer
has a get_mime_string method since build_userdata is only ever
called once so cached get_mime_string results is not needed.
Change-Id: I7cfbcffeea24c9b1f013463f9a5fa53b8c699cfe

commit_message:
VMware: Fix unhandled session failure issues

VMware driver has a re-try mechanism to handle session expiration
failures. Due to a minor bug in the exception handling module, this
failure was unhandled.

The patch fixes this issue and has added tests.

Closes-Bug: #1252827
(cherry picked from commit 6471776b6b25bb4062238f7c1b732b2d6999ec65)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_vmwareapi_vim_util.py

commit_message:
Account for truncated resource names in test PhysName

The utility class PhysName was blindly comparing resource
name without considering that the resource name may
have also been truncated.

Closes-Bug: #1251379

Change-Id: I189f79ee5238b7c82eff1595ef612efb1f8633d4

commit_message:
Fix regression in cloud server tests

Commit 116bd3cb13d76f61fe779b55d5591da671ae471b broke the cloud server contrib
tests because they mocked the default Clients calls instead of the resource's
nova function. This patch adds the correct mocks to the cloud servers tests.

Closes-Bug: #1257947

Change-Id: I904eb9f7e6424603d42b0d59c44e4da16726368c

commit_message:
Make tempest L3 capable plugin aware.

With this patch, the public network config in tempest.conf will be
done for the plugins that support L3.

Change-Id: I820fe300fac45ff92d1281ff0c43ebc137783210

commit_message:
Fixes two doc bugs with networking install and admin

(- ensures network-admin/admin is redirected as people are finding it)
- ensures ubuntu output has ovs install instruction

Not backported: ../www/.htaccess

Change-Id: I22cafaae77e247d8cc2a3d01cd1bfb8320b6efb3
backport: havana
Closes-bug: 1248791
(cherry picked from commit a8ce414fa76a17286cb5fd4bd489378120cfed3e)

commit_message:
port test_server_rescue into v3 part2

This ports test_server_rescue into nova v3 api. And adds
corresponding client support, but this havn't add security
group and floating ip test with server rescue. These will
be added after the corresponding support is added in network
service. Because nova v3 api won't support these.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Ibfbfd07610b6c710d1a49923b8c7d2042e2aa4c9

Check if reboot request type is None

If the reboot request type is None, raise HTTPBadRequest like if the
argument was missing.

Change-Id: I75b1791b7a6c9304c3a78e869fe63d72302fc9d8
Closes-Bug: #1247735

The gate-solum-devstack-dsvm job is now running properly.  It starts up
devstack including solum.  Now we need a suite of tests to run against
solum running in devstack.  This is intended to be the start of that
suite.  The first test is just a request to the root of the API to
verify that version discovery is working (and that we can talk to the
API at all).

Tempest does not have any sort of plugin mechanism, so we can't run in
the context of tempest.  The advice we're given is to just develop our
own functional test suite for now that we can work to integrate later
if/when the project were to become incubated.

Change-Id: Ia6cebf1411a45336ead4442cdc9be4ade4745455
"}]
commit_message:
Add functionaltests directory

The gate-solum-devstack-dsvm job is now running properly.  It starts up
devstack including solum.  Now we need a suite of tests to run against
solum running in devstack.  This is intended to be the start of that
suite.  The first test is just a request to the root of the API to
verify that version discovery is working (and that we can talk to the
API at all).

Tempest does not have any sort of plugin mechanism, so we can't run in
the context of tempest.  The advice we're given is to just develop our
own functional test suite for now that we can work to integrate later
if/when the project were to become incubated.

Change-Id: Ia6cebf1411a45336ead4442cdc9be4ade4745455

Clayton agreed to try to use the Oslo log 'extra' field to create a 'private' section which may be a list of dictionaries of confidential data to filter out before showing lots to end users/customers.  I believe this is an important step early in the project to separate this data out or it will be extremely difficult to add in later.  Just voting -1 until we have a chance to review those changes.  Will work with Adrian on the best way to document these ideas and discuss with the group officially."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-11-25 21:29:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Paul the standard way of preventing things like passwords getting into logs is to star them out like 'password is "******"'. Lets not invent a new logging mechanism, if we need something new then lets add that to oslo first.'}, {'account_id': 9094, 'date': '2013-11-26 15:31:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Angus, this is an effort to identify (for later search filters on the back end) any confidential data that should not to go a customer but may be useful for a Solum administrator.  Recently Ceilometer exposed database passwords because of logging.  I'm hoping to head this off early in the project and set a practice of isolating any confidential data.  An example would be an exception (which may have who knows what in it).  I agree though that passwords (especially plain text) should not be logged.  I am looking at Oslo but any change to that will take a relatively significant amount of time and then we'll have to go back and re-locate confidential data."}, {'account_id': 9094, 'date': '2013-11-26 20:15:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: (2 inline comments)

commit_message:
Import Nova objects code and simplify

Imported nova/objects/base.py and nova/objects/fields.py from nova commit
93efad46aa1cbb9aef68561aca49278ef7584983.

* Renamed Object to DomainObject for better clarity
* Split metataclass behavior and core methods, added register_obj_class(),
  reset_obj_classes(), and obj_class_for_name() to allow easier subclassing
  by complex objects.
* Removed RPC logic (will replace the @remotable syntax with oslo.messaging
  as necessary)
* Removed Nova specific field types

The base code here is now easier to use with subclasses (allowing a consumer
to load and register their own implementations of the base classes)

Change-Id: I26d39d7dcbb4eba10ef6dc853288166d5a7e6699

commit_message:
use six.StringIO for compatibility with io.StringIO in python3

The newer version of six (1.4.1) provides six.StringIO which
is a fake file object for textual data. It's an alias for cStringIO.StringIO,
in python2 and io.StringIO in Python3.

Change-Id: If1ccfca128385f976938f0f0c74573687faad9ac
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Use openstack.common Nova rpc modules.

Nova still supports the nova.rpc locations but they are old school.

Since Nova I9c2f6bdbe8cd0c44417f75284131dbf3c126d1dd (in Jun 2012)
Nova has prefered the use of the openstack common (oslo) drivers
directly.

Change-Id: I6d2ad7584c6b3a30509ae9e1a360e5f53a49448b

commit_message:
Update toci_test.sh support swift in overcloud

With some of the recent changes to the overcloud heat
templates we now make use of Swift in the overcloud.

This updates TOCI to:
 -add swift to the overcloud control images
 -pass heat templates SwiftPassword
 -configure the Swift keystone endpoint

Also, adds a couple other missing elements to the overcloud
image (cinder, dhcp-all-interfaces) which were missing.

Change-Id: I903ecee8dcde6a87a577ea6dcfd7cc935db943c0

commit_message:
Remove dup firewall_driver when using bm driver.

When using the nova BM driver (on the undercloud) we have
a duplicated firewall_driver in our nova.conf file.

This commit removes the nova baremetal specific version since
we alread set it around line 60.

Change-Id: I0b06b72a39463dd978d18d8d76771f49dbbecd64

commit_message:
Enable tasks REST API for async worker

- add REST API layer for async worker(tasks) to
support tasks operations.
- update to include sparse task for tasks.index

Partially implement blueprint async-glance-workers

commit_message:
fakevirt: return hypervisor_version as an int instead of a string

The compute_nodes.hypervisor_version type in the database is an integer
not a string. This is only caught in postgres and not MySQL. Changing
the fakevirt driver to return the proper type allows for the
test_virt_drivers test to make check this for all drivers it currently
tests.

Change-Id: I25e4dba855b954a2451bced9a53172b51eb47238

commit_message:
Sets default service type for Nova V3 API

Set the default service type when talking to the Nova V3 API to
computev3 rather than compute. Although it is rather ugly to have
a different service type for a different version of a service,
this is necessary for the medium term because traditionally the
compute service endpoint has pointed to the V2 API rather than
the root and then version discovery done.

This change allows progression of the V3 API support in
novaclient and although devstack too currently points computev3
directly to the V3 API, the intent is to change this to point to
the root and implement version discovery during the Icehouse
development cycle.

Longer term when the V2 API support is eventually removed we can
reclaim the 'compute' service type and point it to the root.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api

Change-Id: If5d6a0d8af037cde7bf253d71aac2823b89f8066

commit_message:
LVM migrate: Use keywords for the brick instance

In the `migrate_volume` method a new instance is created when the
dest_vg is not equal to the source vg. This new brick instance is
created using positional arguments instead of keywords. However, some of
those arguments are passed in the wrong positions.

This patch uses keywords for the misplaced arguments.

The patch also changes `test_lvm_migrate_volume_proceed` in order to
fully test the happy path and catch things like this.

Closes-bug: #1258128
Change-Id: I75cf91171709554053fd5b52a4aae4e176e8364e

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: Ie0403d702be26e46e7b9ee4e003177cb3bea11aa
Closes-Bug: #1255865

commit_message:
Updates .gitignore

To ignore swap files from getting into repository
currently the implemented ignore is *.swp
however vim adds more swap files if these files exists,
so improving this with *.sw?

Change-Id: Iff581457cabe936b8b285142caff92fcc849f04a
Closes-Bug: #1255876

commit_message:
Fix HTTP response code for network APIs and improve error message

This patch corrects the http response codes for network resources to be
consistant with other resources by returning a 400 instead of a 404
if the desired resource is not found.

This patch makes the following api changes:

v2-api: NetworkNotFound now returns 400 instead of 404 and improved error
        message which network was not found instead of
        'The resource could not be found'.

v3-api: PortNotFound and NetworkNotFound now returns a 400 instead of a 404.

Closes-bug: #1245696

[{'created': '2013-11-22 16:53:11.000000000', 'message': 'Narrow columns used in list_revoked_tokens sql

Currently the SQL backend lists revoked tokens by selecting all of the
columns, including the massive "extra" column. This places a significant
burden on the client library and wastes resources. We only need the
id/expired columns to satisfy the API call.

In tests this query was several orders of magnitude faster with just two
thousand un-expired revoked tokens.

Change-Id: I04d62b98d5d760a3fbc3c8db61530f7ebccb0a48
Closes-Bug: #1253755

commit_message:
Narrow columns used in list_revoked_tokens sql

Currently the SQL backend lists revoked tokens by selecting all of the
columns, including the massive "extra" column. This places a significant
burden on the client library and wastes resources. We only need the
id/expired columns to satisfy the API call.

In tests this query was several orders of magnitude faster with just two
thousand un-expired revoked tokens.

Change-Id: I04d62b98d5d760a3fbc3c8db61530f7ebccb0a48
Closes-Bug: #1253755

commit_message:
Sync openstack.common.local from oslo

`local` has a broken TLS symbol - strong_store, fixed in oslo some time ago in
Ib544be1485823f6c619312fdee5a04031f48bbb4. All direct and indirect
(lockutils and rpc) usages of strong_store might be potentially affected.
Original change to Nova: If4dd973acc23921dbc2bc69bb76225deb2802dad

Closes-Bug: #1254046
Change-Id: I6e5efa156c9a905a979a469244cd483723e6b1e3
(cherry picked from commit e63d30fc6bd4d89b4d394fcfeabb592cbe26881d)

[{'created': '2013-12-06 11:33:46.000000000', 'message': 'Create a shared queue for QPID topic consumers

Fixes bug 1257293

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
ef406a21782134aeefb944f74b3f1a47d6169318

From the oslo-incubator commit:
When multiple RPC servers (consumers) are subscribed to the same RPC
topic, a single RPC request to that topic should be received by only
one of the consumers.  A bug in the QPID driver caused every consumer
to receive a copy of the RPC request.  This bug affects only Topology
version 2.  This patch will cause a single queue to be created for
each topic, and shared among all consumers of that topic.  This
results in each RPC request being received by only one consumer,
in turn across all the competing consumers.

Change-Id: I97c6eb5fe63322ab70716c63074818ff1b6ea82b

commit_message:
Create a shared queue for QPID topic consumers

Fixes bug 1257293

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
e355fa3a9f49ff524ce98d1263a784b5a7929dfb

From the oslo-incubator commit:
When multiple RPC servers (consumers) are subscribed to the same RPC
topic, a single RPC request to that topic should be received by only
one of the consumers.  A bug in the QPID driver caused every consumer
to receive a copy of the RPC request.  This bug affects only Topology
version 2.  This patch will cause a single queue to be created for
each topic, and shared among all consumers of that topic.  This
results in each RPC request being received by only one consumer,
in turn across all the competing consumers.

Change-Id: I97c6eb5fe63322ab70716c63074818ff1b6ea82b

commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

Fixes bug 1251757

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
55678c7ab7fbc1b2beb428d046bb4162f23b0a53

From the oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Change-Id: If966bb25e49b5837293a1bb181bbb02086599d81

commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
e227c0ed7e0ed1f9b8d029336f8aeb60e38c23df

From the oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Change-Id: I563db129e63817ad55165e318f164f06b141ee33
Closes-Bug: 1251757

commit_message:
Adds decorator to deprecate functions and methods

The deprecated decorator logs a deprecation message when the callable it
decorates is used. The message will include the release where the callable
was deprecated, the release where is may be removed and possibly an
optional replacement.

Change-Id: Ic6260ce9d8950afa248c0f7842817e7312a4d5a7

commit_message:
Use cached volumes in REST API extensions

This patch caches db volumes in the core volumes API so that they can be
used in the host and tenant attribute API extensions in order to lower
the response time by avoiding costly individual db queries for each
volume in the REST API contributions.

Change-Id: Ie0cbe929379df32fddbdce1953f13b6f26208bff
Partial-Bug: #1197612
(cherry picked from commit 9ed0f39fceaaa7a56e74055b54b7f6124e9e7f11)

commit_message:
Enable object caching in cinder REST API requests

Allow the core API to cache resources, such as DB results, so that
extensions can use data already retrieved within the same API request
eliminating additional expensive DB calls.

Loosely based on commit 9f9fbc54e7336da10fc3056bdaca2ec7d01c7f94 from
nova.

Change-Id: If9f49faf7305287c0489ad6209cf19b8bec612cc
Partial-Bug: #1197612
(cherry picked from commit 233430b51ddbd207f22eee98386ffbb766fd777f)

commit_message:
Add support to change inteface model (driver)

In order to help with driver testing, this change adds INTERFACE_MODEL
 to the fuelweb_test settings.py and allows for it to be overridden with OS
 environment var of the same name. A quick change of this will cause all
 instances to inherit the same model so it doesn't have to be changed by
 hand.

Requires https://github.com/Mirantis/devops/pull/25

Will work with default of virtio with out devops #25, but all other models
 will require patch or will raise an exception in devops.

Closes-bug #1257513

Change-Id: I778c197a271eda1016b25b630f75e54462b61fb1

Sorry but I'm really not convinced by the approach here.  Scheduler hints are meant to allow a user to specify some abstract constraints around where to place an instance (anti affinity to other instances that they own, etc).  

Allowing a user to influence the general weighting function which is based resource used other instances that don't belong  to the user just feels wrong.    Deciding the rules for how to stack instances is something that should be configured inside the cloud, not changed by the user."}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2013-07-15 02:30:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Phil, are you suggesting that the resource weigher should read 'weighed_resources' and 'weighed_ratios' only from configuration file?"}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2013-07-17 16:23:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm afraid I agree with Phil Day here. This breaks an abstraction layer.

A user should be able to specify a constraint that they would like satisfied for their instance. How the cloud provider chooses to meet that constraint should be entirely transparent. In other words, it should not be apparent to the user how the cloud provider does his job. Putting this in the scheduler hints breaks the abstraction.

The cloud provider sets the weight functions and those weights may take into account a scheduler hint. But the hint should not define the weight function."}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2013-07-18 05:35:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: (2 inline comments)

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-05 08:49:01.000000000', 'message': "Added a new scheduler resource weight plugin.

The new resource weigher can compute the weight based on the compute
node host's various resources. The to-be weighed resources and their
weighting ratio are specified in the 'scheduler_hints' dictionary of
the API request as the followings:

    'os:scheduler_hints': {
        'weighed_resources': ['name1', 'name2']
        'weighed_ratios': ['1.0', '-1.0']
    }

The final weight would be name1.value * 1.0 + name2.value * -1.0.

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling and the
blueprint generic-host-state-for-scheduler.

Change-Id: Ib3e68505e6d4d8f6d67b54c5f00de3e1c172738c

commit_message:
Added a new scheduler metrics weight plugin

The new metrics weigher can compute the weight based on the compute
node host's metrics data. The to-be weighed metrics and their
weighing ratio are specified in the configuration file as the
followings:

    metrics_weight_setting = name1=1.0,name2=-1.0

The final weight would be name1.value * 1.0 + name2.value * (-1.0).

This is part of the blueprint utilization-aware-scheduling.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib3e68505e6d4d8f6d67b54c5f00de3e1c172738c

commit_message:
Retrieve volume image metadata using single query

The image metadata REST API contributions are making an individual db
call for each of the available volumes. When the number of volumes is
large the volume details call can take several minutes.

This patch changes the image metadata API contributions to take
advantage of the new db query to retrieve metadata in bulk.

Change-Id: I9a35438c1f38ea8a3d8f5b687ae58ba1f3f78121
Partial-Bug: #1197612
(cherry picked from commit 56e5805203a14acad78dc806247b5f0f4a22c9f8)

Does this really need to be a separate config file? Why not just merge the contents into the existing l3_agent.ini file? This way, init scripts and systemd units for the l3-agent do not need to have their command lines modified depending on whether or not this service is being used."}, {'account_id': 490, 'date': '2013-12-06 18:32:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Though currently the fwaas driver functionality is leveraged via the hook in the l3_agent, it doesn't need to be this way (say for vendor specific drivers). Hence this configuration was kept in a separate file."}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-12-06 18:53:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

I'm removing my -1 from this patch, since the file itself already does exist and so probably should be packaged by setup.

Config file "fragments" such as fwaas_driver.ini, vpn_agent.ini, ml2_conf_arista.ini and ml2_conf_cisco.ini are creating a problem for OpenStack distributions. Configuration tools (such as puppet modules) need a definitive file in which to set each configuration variable. But OpenStack distributions include (read-only) init scripts and systemd unit files that don't know which options will be used, and thus which files to include in the executable's command lines.'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-12-07 16:05:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

commit_message:
Support uncompressed ipv6 address and abbreviated ipv4 address

Now neutron supports zero-compressed ipv6 address like
'2001:db8::10:10:10:0/120' and unabbreviated ipv4 address
like '10.0.0.0/24'.
This path will make neutron also support uncompressed ipv6
address and abbreviated ipv4 address. for example:
1, uncompressed ipv6 address like 'fe80:0:0:0:0:0:0:0/128'
2, ipv6 address with multiple consecutive zero like
   '2001:0db8:0:0:1::1/128' or '2001::0:1:0:0:1100/120'
3, abbreviated ipv4 address like '10/24'

Change-Id: I755e38ea11c139e15488ec60e7d5682a244ab114
Closes-Bug: #1240790
(cherry picked from commit d1b783fd673448381445dce82e9160ba2f715a7c)

commit_message:
port some flavor tests into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I24b9f5e5159b9c559cdc3677cdb18d5d189dda84

commit_message:
Check HTTP response headers of Swift middleware API in detail

All HTTP response headers of APIs for each Swift middleware are checked
their existence and format as those of Swift 'standard' API are.

Change-Id: I45005861873af66a126a3ebe0b04dd84c9a26eda
Closes-Bug: #1240856

commit_message:
skip test_service_enable_disable

Without locking the test_service_enable_disable can fail with
MismatchError: 'disabled' != u'enabled'
when the xml and json test case runs at the same time.

The another issue with this tast case,
it temporarily disables a random service,
it is unhealthy in a parallel run.

Change-Id: Ibf854c4979c9564dd590a3ced48d88237338b8d9

commit_message:
port test_server_metadata and test_server_personality into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: Ic0029ef8e102755eaa64c01e14f8544f36632376

commit_message:
Ensure NVP API connection port is always an integer

Convert the 'port' part of a NVP endpoint to int before passing
it to the NVP API client.

Change-Id: I15137d943ab950cb5cc80d7af2971bce3ac1a265
Closes-Bug: #1255519

When snapshoting a volume-backed instance, its block device mapping is
copied entirely into the image properties of the resulting snapshot.

commit_message:
Clean BDM when snapshoting volume-backed instances

When snapshoting a volume-backed instance, its block device mapping is
copied entirely into the image properties of the resulting snapshot.

This may lead to some errors when booting from that snapshot because the
fields 'id', 'insance_uuid' and 'connection_info' must be generated for
each instance instead of reusing the ones from the original instance.
For example, sharing the connection_info will cause the new instance to
try to connect to the original volume instead of creating a new one.

This patch cleans all the database-specific plus the connection_info
fields from the block device mapping when creating the snapshot.

Change-Id: I4190e9519d641c61b00b5d86c3885f2ae4fa86f3
Partial-Bug: #1246327
(cherry picked from commit eddd8a14cd2393ce7bdb0ec1c7366177371192b2)

commit_message:
Removed erronus config file comment

The comment stating 'DHCP agents needs it.' with regards to the
rpc_notifier notification_driver is incorrect.  Looking through
the code, I see no place this is true.  I believe it to be an
error.

Closes-Bug: #1258390

Change-Id: I58c2f9290731f3e88e4b4a5bdb600aa5bac1a12b

'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-25 13:41:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

One problem I see with this is that it won't work for updates of the provider stack - so you can update your template using the same provider, but you can't update your provider without changing the URL. I'm not sure if that's what we want or not.

This seems like fixing the problem in the wrong place - surely the environment should provide us with the template file? It should store any files that are passed in the database and be able to regurgitate them. (It could also pre-fetch any URLs and store the results of those in the DB too, although TBH I think we should probably remove support for fetching arbitrary URLs in the engine on security grounds.) The final piece in the puzzle is automatic client-side inclusion of any necessary files with the create/update request."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-11-25 23:51:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thanks Zane, awesome feedback as always.

I'll fix the update (yes we need to update with just parameter changes).

re: generically storing files and retrieving them
I agree we need *something*, I'd prefer to punt to swift
so when we get the files section just post to swift/object-api, arguably we should do that with the main template too (are we in the business of storing files?)."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-11-26 12:08:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It'd be great to be able to punt to Swift, but I'm wary of having a dependency on it. It makes development more difficult, complicates stand-alone mode and has billing implications for the user.

Maybe add a separate 'files' table in the database? It's icky, I know :/"}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-11-27 10:52:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-11-27 11:32:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

commit_message:
Fix stack-show on a TemplateResource with outputs

TemplateResource currently tries to re-download the template.
this is not good, esp. if you have a relative path to a local file.
First see if we have a new template, if not look in the db.

Closes-bug: #1252980
Change-Id: If819aab9ed1360744f8e73f0b6409641e2d8114f

VirtualDiskManager.DeleteVirtualDisk_Task API, which allows the picking

commit_message:
VMware: fix snapshot failure when host in maintenance mode

The root cause is due to a bug in the VC's handling of the
VirtualDiskManager.DeleteVirtualDisk_Task API, which allows the picking
of any host in a datacenter with access to the datastore participating
in the disk deletion picked be to perform the operation, even when the
host is in maintenance mode and hence will always reject the call when
sent.

The fix uses an alternative API (FileManager.DeleteDatastoreFile_Task)
to delete the vmdk and -flat vmdk files separately. This API does not
suffer from the above-mentioned failure mode.

Closes-Bug: #1229994

(cherry picked from commit 7910385825ccfa705785af360fcd5717656e3557)

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/fake.py
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/vmops.py

Change-Id: I786365847673e5192a21b654cba951b2e7a6f291

[{'created': '2013-11-29 22:02:01.000000000', 'message': "Add transport aliases

We need to support deprecated transport driver configurations like:

 rpc_backend = nova.rpc.impl_kombu

i.e. 'nova.rpc.impl_kombu' is a deprecated alias for 'rabbit'.

Initially, we supported this by adding the aliases to each project's
setup.cfg:

oslo.messaging.drivers =
    nova.rpc.impl_kombu = oslo.messaging._drivers.impl_rabbit:RabbitDriver

However, this means that code like this:

  url = str(TransportURL(conf))

generates a bogus URL string like:

  nova.rpc.impl_kombu://...

We need to apply these transport aliases when we load drivers, but also
when we create transport URLs from configuration containing potentially
deprecated aliases.

To enable that, add a transport_aliases parameter to to TransportURL(),
TransportURL.parse() and get_transport().

blueprint: transport-aliases

commit_message:
Add transport aliases

We need to support deprecated transport driver configurations like:

 rpc_backend = nova.rpc.impl_kombu

i.e. 'nova.rpc.impl_kombu' is a deprecated alias for 'rabbit'.

Initially, we supported this by adding the aliases to each project's
setup.cfg:

oslo.messaging.drivers =
    nova.rpc.impl_kombu = oslo.messaging._drivers.impl_rabbit:RabbitDriver

However, this means that code like this:

  url = str(TransportURL(conf))

generates a bogus URL string like:

  nova.rpc.impl_kombu://...

We need to apply these transport aliases when we load drivers, but also
when we create transport URLs from configuration containing potentially
deprecated aliases.

To enable that, add an aliases parameter to TransportURL(),
TransportURL.parse() and get_transport().

blueprint: transport-aliases
Change-Id: Ifce68ff62746c2a363c719417a2bd0a78ee025dd

commit_message:
LVM: Activate source LV before cloning from it

LVM may be configured to not automatically activate
thin-provisioned LVs.

Ensure they are activated when performing a clone, otherwise
dd will fail as the device does not exist in /dev/mapper/.

Closes-Bug: #1252423

'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-12-02 21:45:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

So... the old behavior wasn't that great.

Basically we used to just pass through whatever you gave as headers to httplib which would convert whatever it was to a string.  So when I send in 'x-object-meta-nothing': None we're letting it pass through and httplib will convert it to 'x-object-meta-nothing': 'None'.

Which probably no one expects, but that's the way standard lib works - and with the type None this change works that way too.

But I think ultimately the original change just missed the mark by expecting type coercion earlier than necessary.  For me this would have been better:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/54314/

In addition to restoring the old/odd behavior for None it fixes slightly less esoteric regressions like a TypeError when you send in content-length as an int through the headers kwarg instead of content_length kwarg:

http://paste.openstack.org/show/54316/"}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2013-12-02 22:12:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

yeah right, I was actually thinking the same thing that this morning on my way to work but i forgot to update it (if it's a float/integer it would crash as well)

commit_message:
Don't crash when header is value of None

Before commit 7d88d14d (http://git.io/hhJWdQ) swifclient used to accept
header value with the type None :

{'Headers': None}

It would just be happy with it with those None headers and not process
them, reinstate the old behavior.

Closes-Bug: 1256441
Change-Id: Ic7f80c38ef2ce9ef1687ed0d6d65521f2e754905

commit_message:
Clean up useless ex variable

When handle exception, if the exception was not used, then there is
no need to use "except Exception as ex", just using "except ValueError"
is good enough.

Change-Id: I495e239cbca20246cb88da166a80bbd4eda1a094

commit_message:
Makes tasks owner not nullable in models.py

The tasks table scheme in migration for adding tasks to Glance DB has a
flag for disabling from setting a NULL owner.

In order to keep the behavior consistent across the glance codebase,
this patch adds owner as not nullable in the models.py.

Fixes bug: 1257949

Change-Id: Id9fff4277f427b7d83d80b5a0a8029968f70e0df

commit_message:
Add request timeout handling for Mellanox Neutron Agent

Add request timeout handling for messages sent to eswitch Daemon.
Using configurable number of retries and increasing waiting interval
between retries resend the message.
If request timeout persists, eswitch daemon is not reachable.
In such case, exit the agent process.

Closes-Bug: #1228827

Change-Id: If1290bedafe7a0dd8a61cbe328510075edeb1e5b

commit_message:
Prevent early auth deny in tempauth when using swift3 middleware.

When tempauth is used together with swift3 and keystone, groups are
empty and tempauth denies the request too early without a chance for
keystone to authenticate the request.

Change-Id: I21d9b22ecbd18a5f1fba901abd94221a332c45ea
Closes-Bug: 1244545

commit_message:
Deleting statistics tables from resource usage page

The tables were interpreting the stats in a wrong way, for some stats
it's not even easily possible to get those stats. We need to go through
each statistic separately and document it in the Ceilometer docs first.

Then it's more likely that these table stats will be distributed in
various tables in dashboard in the form of sparklines so these pages
won't be needed.

Fixes bug 1249279

Conflicts:
	openstack_dashboard/api/ceilometer.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tabs.py
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/metering/tests.py

Change-Id: Ib8c110f5d66fae50df12f8f0beeb99c2b2d00bf6

commit_message:
Allow access to the in-memory object server

This will allow functional tests to be used against it, and can then
be used for the storage-policy work as an example diskfile
implementation associated with a storage policy.

Change-Id: I47a88e70cee99225779baaed379b0c5d4c73611a

contribution is making an individual db call for each of the available

This patch adds a call to the volume.API to retrieve image metadata in

commit_message:
Add call to retrieve image metadata for volumes in bulk

When using the GET volume details REST API call, the image metadata API
contribution is making an individual db call for each of the available
volumes. When the number of volumes is large the details call can take
several minutes.

This patch adds a call to the volume.API to retrieve image metadata in
bulk, very similar to the one used to retrieve individual volume image
metadata.

Change-Id: Ic3aa721016704c72b7564cc5ceff71676806a24a
Partial-Bug: #1197612
(cherry picked from commit bb2daca2864a5607635a3aa37f3874fdda22797b)

[{'created': '2013-12-05 06:37:29.000000000', 'message': 'Fix changes-since filter for list-servers API

On list-servers API, "changes-since" parameter filters out servers
which have been created at the same date as the specified timestamp.
For example, the following server is filtered out with "changes-since=
2013-12-05T15:03:25":

  mysql> select display_name, updated_at from instances;
  +--------------+---------------------+
  | display_name | updated_at          |
  +--------------+---------------------+
  | vm01         | 2013-12-05 15:03:25 |
  +--------------+---------------------+

The behavior would be wrong from the viewpoint of its name which
includes "since". This patch chanegs the server list for including
the ones created at the specified timestamp.

Change-Id: Icc10a1363503b3553d810c6be20b86b3da7ac1a0
Related-Bug: #1236585

commit_message:
Fix changes-since filter for list-servers API

On list-servers API, "changes-since" parameter filters out servers
which have been created at the same date as the specified timestamp.
For example, the following server is filtered out with "changes-since=
2013-12-05T15:03:25":

  mysql> select display_name, updated_at from instances;
  +--------------+---------------------+
  | display_name | updated_at          |
  +--------------+---------------------+
  | vm01         | 2013-12-05 15:03:25 |
  +--------------+---------------------+

This bug causes some Tempest test failures, if the timestamp of server
creations are the same as the "changes-since" timestamp in second unit.
In addition, the behavior would be wrong from the viewpoint of its name
which includes "since".

This patch chanegs the server list for including the ones created at
the specified timestamp.

Change-Id: Icc10a1363503b3553d810c6be20b86b3da7ac1a0
Closes-Bug: #1236585

commit_message:
Fix install_get_pip in order to work behind a proxy

Proxy envvars are not passed to pip when sudo, we need to export
them.

Change-Id: I67622f5ea8ecb948006e032bdc395ecf36914146
Closes-Bug: #1258155

commit_message:
Add Ceph as backup backend support

Cinder backup could use Ceph as backend.
This patch aims to create cinder::backup::ceph class to use this driver.

Change-Id: Ib82b94f3e2d5d9e2287a570a435d469656c9a756
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Add metering agent support

The Ceilometer project is able to get meters from Neutron via the
notifications system on how much bandwidth the projects are using.
The idea is to meter this as the L3 routers levels.

The feature exists since Havana.

Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
implement blueprint metering-agent

Change-Id: I62ad9b7455e5f2bc3455b55a346f2515ca1040a3

commit_message:
Add an editorconfig file

EditorConfig helps developers define and maintain consistent coding
styles between different editors and IDEs. The EditorConfig project
consists of a file format for defining coding styles and a collection
of text editor plugins that enable editors to read the file format and
adhere to defined styles. EditorConfig files are easily readable and
they work nicely with version control systems.

Plugins for editorconfig are available for almost all IDEs, official
website http://editorconfig.org/

Change-Id: I711c4204356d94b0639c0b1907029e7eccd216c5

commit_message:
Continuation of NodeJS POC, less support

    Add less support and new command line behaviour, now typing:
"runserver -g" launch a grunt task, available tasks are:
    - jshint : perform a jshint check over all js files
    - jshint --file=filename: perform a jshint check over files
        which are matching filename
    - less: perform a less compilation on files located into
        openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/less/ (even the css)
    - dev: run a dev environment, this environment will check at file
        changes in openstack_dashboard/static/dashboard/less/ and
        openstack_dashboard/static/bootstrap/less/, when a change occurs
        a less compilation is run.

Change-Id: Ie8354db6f5fed3c866e10580be88a9114eb2b502

[{'created': '2013-11-26 13:59:22.000000000', 'message': 'Little POC of Node integration into Horizon

    This little POC show the integration of Node and its task runner
Grunt into Horizon architecture. In this POC I have just integrated
Node in the run_test.sh script, if you run ./run_test.sh -j it will
perform a simple jshint syntax check on all horizon js files. If you
type ./run_test.sh -j --file filename, it will perform a jshint check
just on the file specified (it is based on javascript indexOf function,
if you type "--file chart" it will check d3piechart.js and
d3linechart.js).

    Nothing needed, if node and grunt are not installed, they will be
automatically downloaded and added.

    This POC demonstrate the power of Grunt and how easy it is to add
task into it (30 lines to integrate jshint with a powerfull filter).

    It is important to notice that it already exists a lot of plugins
for testing, csslint, less compiler, angular testing. I will make some
patches for the other tools (especially for unit tests). You can check
the Grunt documentation for further informations: http://gruntjs.com/

commit_message:
Little POC of Node integration into Horizon

    This little POC show the integration of Node and its task runner
Grunt into Horizon architecture. In this POC I have just integrated
Node in the run_test.sh script, if you run ./run_test.sh -j it will
perform a simple jshint syntax check on all horizon js files. If you
type ./run_test.sh -j --file filename, it will perform a jshint check
just on the file specified (it is based on javascript indexOf function,
if you type "--file chart" it will check d3piechart.js and
d3linechart.js).

    Nothing needed, if node and grunt are not installed, they will be
automatically downloaded and added.

    This POC demonstrate the power of Grunt and how easy it is to add
task into it (30 lines to integrate jshint with a powerfull filter).

    It is important to notice that it already exists a lot of plugins
for testing, csslint, less compiler, angular testing. I will make some
patches for the other tools (especially for unit tests). You can check
the Grunt documentation for further informations: http://gruntjs.com/

Change-Id: I4e15e284dbd35bdfb8a91e8b9aaf6cf7f81235d6

Before I really get started digging into this ... I don't understand the premise here

You want to allow passing None for conf? The drivers don't support this, they all require a ConfigOpts object

Is this part of a series of changes where the drivers will work without a ConfigOpts object?

And, again, what's the use case? What concrete, known API user is going to use this API without passing a config object?"}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-29 11:07:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 1247, 'date': '2013-11-29 11:15:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (2 inline comments)

Bear with my while I waffle about control_exchange a little bit ... I know I probably seem to be overthinking this, but the tl;dr is I think I'd add a default_exchange kwarg to get_transport() rather than supporting exchange as a transport URL parameter

---

The exchange thing is slightly weird. It is an attribute of Target, which means it's about how remote call is addressed. But it's the only one of those attributes which can be set in the configuration file.

The only sensible reason for it to be configurable by users is as a bucket or namespace for all of the targets in a single service to live. The use case would be if you want host e.g. two instances of Nova on the same message bus. But even that is broken right now (see bug #1173552) and so we just use vhosts to separate services when needed. The only case where this hurts us now is that Cinder can't call its scheduler topic 'cinder' because that clashes with Nova even though they both have different values for control_exchange.

OTOH, the transport URL values are all about connecting to a message bus, not about how remote calls are addressed. So, on that basis, I wonder whether it belongs in the transport URL.

The use case I most think about for transport URLs is something which needs to connect to many different services which are potentially on different message buses - it would have a list of services and a transport URL for each would give enough info to connect to the bus that the service is on. However, the Target attributes describing how calls should be addressed wouldn't come from the transport URL, they'd be listed separately.

Imagine if you just wanted to code something which pinged a bunch of services. It would be configured with something like this:

  services = {
    "nova-scheduler" : dict(target=dict(exchange='nova',
					topic='scheduler'),
                            transport_url='qpid://...'),
    "cinder-scheduler" : dict(target=dict(exchange='cinder',
                                          topic='cinder-scheduler'),
                              transport_url='qpid://...'),
  }

This is also why the value of conf.control_exchange is passed to the transport driver as 'default_exchange' - it's basically just a handy default to use where a Target object doesn't have the exchange value set.'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-11-29 11:22:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: (1 inline comment)

Hi Nikola,

TBH - I don't think this is a good fix. It seems rather arbitrary, and putting another _destroy call at the end seems like it will just reduce the chance of a race problem (if that) and not really eliminate it.
--- I believe this patch can eliminate the race problem fully, because if the instance files(actually the disk files) are deleted, then the instance will have no chance to be started again. So if we check and destroy it after deleting the disk files, the race problem will be fixed.
There is already a similar check in _destroy method, and adding this just seems like adding cruft code without addressing the real issue.

A more reasonable approach to fixing this particular race would be to back out of a reboot on delete, but that does not seem as easy to implement, from a quick glance.
--- yes, this is a good idea, but as you know it is really not so easy to implement, this is not only because the coding but also beacuse the design guide of the driver(if I'm right, we have to query the nova db to get the instance vm/task state to know whether the instance is deleted/in deleting, and this is a bad idea to query db at virt driver level)"}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2013-11-27 10:37:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
libvirt: Fix race cond between reboot and delete

The race condition is that, if we soft reboot an instance, and then
terminate it, then the instance may wait for shutdown status in the
'reboot' thread, and if the 'terminate' thread destroy the instance,
but has not deleted the instance disk files, the instance may be
started by 'reboot' thread again, and then it becomes to a running
deleted one.

Closes-Bug: #1246181

Change-Id: I2fe102e68afffaa0858a3e5b5807aeedf7f0ead9

[{'created': '2013-11-29 12:20:43.000000000', 'message': "Bump the upper bound of SQLAlchemy version number

Currently, we are bound to SQLAlchemy 0.7.x branch in
global-requirements.txt. This was mostly due to the fact
that sqlalchemy-migrate version on PyPi didn't support
SQLAlchemy 0.8.x branch. But a few weeks ago we released
a new version of sqlalchemy-migrate which does support
SQLAlchemy 0.8.x releases.

We should bump the SQLAlchemy version in global-requirements
in order to make our CI environment closer to real deployments
(as distros have been providing SQLAlchemy 0.8.x with patched
version of sqlalchemy-migrate for some time now).

This has been tested by running of unit tests of core OpenStack
projects using SQLAlchemy version bumped to 0.8.x in projects own
requirements.txt files.

Change-Id: Ia587f9def612a3e20e6ecea0c5e30f53ea136f2e
"}]
commit_message:
Bump the upper bound of SQLAlchemy version number

Currently, we are bound to SQLAlchemy 0.7.x branch in
global-requirements.txt. This was mostly due to the fact
that sqlalchemy-migrate version on PyPi didn't support
SQLAlchemy 0.8.x branch. But a few weeks ago we released
a new version of sqlalchemy-migrate which does support
SQLAlchemy 0.8.x releases.

We should bump the SQLAlchemy version in global-requirements
in order to make our CI environment closer to real deployments
(as distros have been providing SQLAlchemy 0.8.x with patched
version of sqlalchemy-migrate for some time now).

This has been tested by running of unit tests of core OpenStack
projects using SQLAlchemy version bumped to 0.8.x in projects own
requirements.txt files.

Change-Id: Ia587f9def612a3e20e6ecea0c5e30f53ea136f2e

commit_message:
NvpApiException should return str

NvpApiException can inherit from NeutronException
NeutronException.__str__ should return str of message
attribute.

Fixes Bug #1228969
Change-Id: I9b2d27b2effbd238416a3ba33b981925f34ac12a

Ah, I see.  Nova has their own implementation of this filter.

I guess I'm still inclined to leave it in for now.  I see Cinder is using it by default (https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/etc/cinder/cinder.conf.sample#L950), so it's not dead code and there's a reasonable chance another service might want to use the availability zone idea for scheduling.  In fact, there's the new external scheduler project just getting started that might want to use this since they won't be as tightly integrated with the Nova db (I would think anyway).

commit_message:
Remove AvailabilityZoneFilter from oslo

AvailabilityZoneFilter is not a common filter for both nova and
cinder. As in nova, AvailabilityZoneFilter need to access nova db
to get host aggregation metadata but cinder do not have host
aggregation concept for now.

Change-Id: I7fdd62f881c0c9d2ce9dffed08781ac4c88333ba
Closes-Bug: #1253574

commit_message:
Sqlalchemy pool settings for ceilometer

Change sqlalchemy pool settings for ceilometer:
* max_pool_size=10
* max_overflow=20

The previous values was 5/10 that is not enought to record samples
produced during a full tempest tests in gate.

Fixes bug #1243251

Change-Id: Id30f787596bce0802eb48ae164e4b31e47b17cf2

Sync local from oslo.

local has a broken TLS symbol - strong_store - in Nova today, fixed in oslo
some time ago in Ib544be1485823f6c619312fdee5a04031f48bbb4

Change-Id: If4dd973acc23921dbc2bc69bb76225deb2802dad
Closes-Bug: #1251920
(cherry picked from commit 9b44d9d75d3767c6b7d1af4f237da8c1cf16266a)

commit_message:
Document when config options were deprecated

When going through the code and looking for what code was deprecated and
when, its easier to know if there is an explicit comment. Otherwise one
has to trace through 'git log' and 'git blame' to be 100% sure that its
ok to remove the code.

Change-Id: I57b5861e57168c44729934757e732de962f3d91a

commit_message:
Libvirt: Adding video device to instances

Adding a video device driver to an instance, when VNC or SPICE are enabled.
Selecting the qxl driver when SPICE is enabled, otherwise use the Libvirt default, cirrus.

Implements blueprint libvirt-video-driver-selection
Change-Id: Icc3c538f2b81cc242baf87dc3538c27daf96ec38

Configuration element for describing video drivers.

The configuration is needed to allow the users to select
a non default video driver.

Partially implements blueprint libvirt-video-driver-selection

commit_message:
Remove traces of V3 personality extension from api samples

Removes occurences of the personality extension from the V3 API
samples as the extension has been removed. Cleanup of consistency
of image and flavor ref examples for the api samples.

DocImpact

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-remove-extensions

Change-Id: I43a34097904d3d7e280039c3d5d76479a49e92d0

commit_message:
Removes os-personalities extension from the V3 API

As per the discussion on the mailing list here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-September/015490.html

and discussions at summit, this patch removes the os-personalities
from the V3 API.

DocImpact

Part of blueprint v3-api-remove-extensions

commit_message:
Compact pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 160.

Compacts the pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 160 into a
single migration (160_havana.py).

Pre-Icehouse users will now need to upgrade to Havana before
running any Icehouse migrations.

Tested on MySQL and PostgreSQL schemas on Fedora 19 to ensure the
new compacted migration generates an identical schema to the
previous migrate scripts in Havana.

Specific changes include:

 1) Make task_log period_begining, period_ending a DateTime.

 2) Change type of deleted column.

 3) Create shadow tables.

 4) Add task log unique constraint.

 5) Add security_group_default_rules table.

 6) Add networks unique constraint.

 7) Revert ip column length.

NOTE: This patch removes the 184_sqlite_upgrade.sql and
184_sqlite_downgrade.sql migrations since these were causing
new test failures and the standard DB migration seems to take
care of it.

Implements: blueprint compact-havana-db-migrations

Change-Id: If977e5f02fffbfb1bc257b3beddf2d7133e6c7b9

[{'created': '2013-10-30 16:22:51.000000000', 'message': 'Compact pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 150.

Compacts the pre-Icehouse database less <= 150 migrations into a
single migration (150_havana.py).

Pre-Icehouse users will now need to upgrade to Havana before
running any Icehouse migrations.

Tested on MySQL and PostgreSQL schemas on Fedora 19 to ensure the
new compacted migration generates an identical schema to the
previous migrate scripts in Havana.

Specific changes include:

 1) Make migrations.instance_uuid a String 36.

 2) Add migrations_instance_uuid_and_status_idx index.

 3) rename instance info caches seq (postgresql only, dropped from
    baseline)

 4) Add source_node, dest_node columns to migrations. Indexes...

 5) Add new volume usage cache table.

 6) Drop aggregates.availability_zone column.

 7) Drop services.availability_zone column.

 8) Add instance actions tables.

 9) Convert PostgreSQL to INET.

 10) Add host to instance faults.

Implements: blueprint compact-havana-db-migrations

Change-Id: Ic0c318967b69af32536b5ab6999affc7755ec442

commit_message:
Compact pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 150.

Compacts the pre-Icehouse database migrations <= 150 into a
single migration (150_havana.py).

Pre-Icehouse users will now need to upgrade to Havana before
running any Icehouse migrations.

Tested on MySQL and PostgreSQL schemas on Fedora 19 to ensure the
new compacted migration generates an identical schema to the
previous migrate scripts in Havana.

Specific changes include:

 1) Make migrations.instance_uuid a String 36.

 2) Add migrations_instance_uuid_and_status_idx index.

 3) rename instance info caches seq (postgresql only, dropped from
    baseline)

 4) Add source_node, dest_node columns to migrations. Indexes...

 5) Add new volume usage cache table.

 6) Drop aggregates.availability_zone column.

 7) Drop services.availability_zone column.

 8) Add instance actions tables.

 9) Convert PostgreSQL to INET.

 10) Add host to instance faults.

Implements: blueprint compact-havana-db-migrations

Change-Id: Ic0c318967b69af32536b5ab6999affc7755ec442

commit_message:
Don't log stacktrace for UnexpectedTaskStateError

An UnexpectedTaskStateError is actually an expected behavior and we
don't need to log a stacktrace every time it happens. This stacktrace
is one of the most common ones found in nova-compute during gating jobs.

The parameter of agent update API has been changed from "para" to
"agent" since Nova v3 API, and this patch fixes the sample doc.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-specification

commit_message:
Fix sample parameter of agent API

The parameter of agent update API has been changed from "para" to
"agent" since Nova v3 API, and this patch fixes the sample doc.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-specification

Change-Id: Ic9c0f11a637e48daa9457ab9ae923fefc0fb350d

commit_message:
Cells: check states on resize/rebuild updates

When the API cell receives instance updates, check the task states for
any resize and rebuild states.  Make sure to only apply them if the
current task state for the instance is what we expect.  This will fix
any out of order messages from potentially stomping on re-setting the
instance to ACTIVE/None on finish of the actions.

Change-Id: Id79e35e29170ac2b8f42a955cecaae3072aba09c
Closes-bug: 1249072

commit_message:
Make flavor_access extension use Flavor object

This makes the flavor_access extensions use the Flavor object instead
of calling into the compute/flavors.py file entirely.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: I360c28ad2a239b34822ba9dda3b5c583c8c886b3

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-06 03:12:54.000000000', 'message': "Stop mutating PATH_INFO in proxy server

The proxy server was calling swob.Request.path_info_pop() prior to
instantiating a controller so that req.path_info was just /a/c/o (sans
/v1). The version got moved over into SCRIPT_NAME.

This lead to some unfortunate behavior when trying to re-use a request
from middleware. Something like this:

    # Imagine we're a WSGIContext object here.
    #
    # To start, SCRIPT_NAME = '' and PATH_INFO='/v1/a/c/o'

    resp_iter = self._app_call(env, start_response)
    # Now SCRIPT_NAME='/v1' and PATH_INFO ='/a/c/o'

    if something_special in self._response_headers:
        env['REQUEST_METHOD'] = 'GET'
        env.pop('HTTP_RANGE', None)

	# 404 SURPRISE! The proxy calls path_info_pop() again,
        # and now SCRIPT_NAME='/v1/a' and PATH_INFO='/c/o', so this
        # gets treated as a container request. Yikes.
        resp_iter = self._app_call(env, start_response)

Now we just leave SCRIPT_NAME and PATH_INFO alone. To make life easy
for everyone who does want just /a/c/o, I defined
swob.Request.swift_entity_path, which just strips off the /v1.

Note that there's still one call to path_info_pop() in tempauth, but
that's only for requests going to /auth, so it won't affect Swift API
requests. It might be a good idea to remove that one later, but let's
do one thing at a time.

Change-Id: I87557a11c01f3f3889b610578cda6ba7d3933e7a
"}, {'created': '2013-12-06 19:04:00.000000000', 'message': "Stop mutating PATH_INFO in proxy server

commit_message:
Stop mutating PATH_INFO in proxy server

The proxy server was calling swob.Request.path_info_pop() prior to
instantiating a controller so that req.path_info was just /a/c/o (sans
/v1). The version got moved over into SCRIPT_NAME.

This lead to some unfortunate behavior when trying to re-use a request
from middleware. Something like this:

    # Imagine we're a WSGIContext object here.
    #
    # To start, SCRIPT_NAME = '' and PATH_INFO='/v1/a/c/o'

    resp_iter = self._app_call(env, start_response)
    # Now SCRIPT_NAME='/v1' and PATH_INFO ='/a/c/o'

    if something_special in self._response_headers:
        env['REQUEST_METHOD'] = 'GET'
        env.pop('HTTP_RANGE', None)

	# 404 SURPRISE! The proxy calls path_info_pop() again,
        # and now SCRIPT_NAME='/v1/a' and PATH_INFO='/c/o', so this
        # gets treated as a container request. Yikes.
        resp_iter = self._app_call(env, start_response)

Now we just leave SCRIPT_NAME and PATH_INFO alone. To make life easy
for everyone who does want just /a/c/o, I defined
swob.Request.swift_entity_path, which just strips off the /v1.

Note that there's still one call to path_info_pop() in tempauth, but
that's only for requests going to /auth, so it won't affect Swift API
requests. It might be a good idea to remove that one later, but let's
do one thing at a time.

[{'created': '2013-12-03 01:42:45.000000000', 'message': "Update handoff algorithm to use IP/port pairs

The replica placement algorithm works on regions, then zones, then
IP/port, then device ID. The handoff algorithm worked on regions, then
zones, then device ID, completely skipping IP/port. It's now been
updated to take IP/port into consideration.

This means you get one handoff on each machine in the cluster before
you start getting handoffs that share a machine with a previous
one. In small clusters, this can help with durability.

Because this is performance-critical code, here are some quick
benchmark results:

Run time averages over 25000 trials on a 1200-device ring (20 part
power, 3 replicas, 2 regions, 10 zones, 120 nodes):

		   |   master    |   branch
===================+=============+============
get 1 more node	   |  2.727e-05	 |  3.076e-05
get 6 more nodes   |  3.55e-05   |  4.214e-05
get all more nodes |  0.002247   |  0.002691

There's a small slowdown from the additional bookkeeping, but nothing
too awful. The time to get 6 more nodes (for handoff checks on 404,
it's 2x replica count by default, hence 6) went from 35 to 42
microseconds, so it remains small.

Change-Id: Ie7da4dfcb0fcf1a38e2fb13f60c204540fadbf06
"}]
commit_message:
Update handoff algorithm to use IP/port pairs

The replica placement algorithm works on regions, then zones, then
IP/port, then device ID. The handoff algorithm worked on regions, then
zones, then device ID, completely skipping IP/port. It's now been
updated to take IP/port into consideration.

This means you get one handoff on each machine in the cluster before
you start getting handoffs that share a machine with a previous
one. In small clusters, this can help with durability.

Because this is performance-critical code, here are some quick
benchmark results:

Run time averages over 25000 trials on a 1200-device ring (20 part
power, 3 replicas, 2 regions, 10 zones, 120 nodes):

		   |   master    |   branch
===================+=============+============
get 1 more node	   |  2.727e-05	 |  3.076e-05
get 6 more nodes   |  3.55e-05   |  4.214e-05
get all more nodes |  0.002247   |  0.002691

There's a small slowdown from the additional bookkeeping, but nothing
too awful. The time to get 6 more nodes (for handoff checks on 404,
it's 2x replica count by default, hence 6) went from 35 to 42
microseconds, so it remains small.

Change-Id: Ie7da4dfcb0fcf1a38e2fb13f60c204540fadbf06

commit_message:
VMware: Fix unhandled session failure issues

VMware driver has a re-try mechanism to handle session expiration
failures. Due to a minor bug in the exception handling module, this
failure was unhandled.

The patch fixes this issue and has added tests.

Closes-Bug: #1252827
Change-Id: Ie91adb4b4b57b7cefeed855cdbe4710da86294f0

commit_message:
Opt out of the service catalog

Set include_servce_catalog=False in Keystone's auth_token
example configuration. Swift does not use X-Service-Catalog
so there is no need to suffer its overhead. In addition,
service catalogs can be larger than max_header_size so this
change avoids a failure mode.

DocImpact
Relates to bug 1228317

Change-Id: If94531ee070e4a47cbd9b848d28e2313730bd3c0

[{'created': '2013-12-03 22:59:27.000000000', 'message': "Preserve closeability of app iterables in WSGIContext

PEP 333 (WSGI) says that if your iterable has a close() method, the
framework must call it.

WSGIContext._app_call pulls the first chunk off the returned iterable
to make sure that it gets status and headers, and then it would
itertools.chain() that first chunk back onto the iterable so the whole
body went out.

The problem is that an itertools.chain object doesn't have a close()
method, so your iterable's fancy-pants close() method has no chance of
getting called.

This patch adds a slightly smarter CloseableChain that works like
itertools.chain, but has a close() method that calls the underlying
iterables' close() methods, if any.

Change-Id: If975c93f53c27dfa0c2f52f4bbf599af25202f70
"}, {'created': '2013-12-04 00:06:20.000000000', 'message': "Preserve closeability of app iterables

PEP 333 (WSGI) says that if your iterable has a close() method, the
framework must call it.

WSGIContext._app_call pulls the first chunk off the returned iterable
to make sure that it gets status and headers, and then it would
itertools.chain() that first chunk back onto the iterable so the whole
body went out. swob.Response.call_application() does it too.

The problem is that an itertools.chain object doesn't have a close()
method, so your iterable's fancy-pants close() method has no chance of
getting called.

This patch adds a slightly smarter CloseableChain that works like
itertools.chain, but has a close() method that calls the underlying
iterables' close() methods, if any.

Change-Id: If975c93f53c27dfa0c2f52f4bbf599af25202f70
"}]
commit_message:
Preserve closeability of app iterables

PEP 333 (WSGI) says that if your iterable has a close() method, the
framework must call it.

WSGIContext._app_call pulls the first chunk off the returned iterable
to make sure that it gets status and headers, and then it would
itertools.chain() that first chunk back onto the iterable so the whole
body went out. swob.Response.call_application() does it too.

The problem is that an itertools.chain object doesn't have a close()
method, so your iterable's fancy-pants close() method has no chance of
getting called.

This patch adds a slightly smarter CloseableChain that works like
itertools.chain, but has a close() method that calls the underlying
iterables' close() methods, if any.

Change-Id: If975c93f53c27dfa0c2f52f4bbf599af25202f70

If the certfile or keyfile is missing or Designate doesn't have
permission to read them, nsd4slave would throw a cryptic SSL exception
when it tried to connect to the NSD4 servers. To avoid this, make sure
that the certfile and keyfile are readable upon backend init and raise a
human-readable exception if they're not.

Change-Id: I837cd328cf31f568e5da4ad4edf8c4dd34ddf8e2
"}]
commit_message:
Make sure that certfile and keyfile are readable

If the certfile or keyfile is missing or Designate doesn't have
permission to read them, nsd4slave would throw a cryptic SSL exception
when it tried to connect to the NSD4 servers. To avoid this, make sure
that the certfile and keyfile are readable upon backend init and raise a
human-readable exception if they're not.

Change-Id: I837cd328cf31f568e5da4ad4edf8c4dd34ddf8e2

commit_message:
Don't fix disks before rexecing

Do _even less_ before the rexec.  Only use the copy of devstack-gate
in the workspace, don't put it in DEST (/opt/stack/...), that way
it doesn't interfere with anything that happens with /opt later.

Change-Id: Ie1a146c6948316593506c02026136e245dc4b31d

commit_message:
Set the rpc control_exchange "again"

rpc_set_default() is never called, since all the config
opts always registed just do this globally.

Change-Id: I277318ec5e903074976ee39460d8583505a723a4
Closes-bug: #1257595

How? This makes no sense. you can still cherrypick commits as you want, this just takes our version to the latest.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2013-12-06 18:34:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

Angus,

The reason I -1 this change is I wanted a cherry-pick of the particular patch from master.

Steve Hardy and I had a discussion on IRC today about our workflow relating to handling backports to stable/grizzly.

The outcome of that was the following workflow when an issue pops up in the common code:

Run update.py on code base
cherry-pick from oslo-incubator the specific change into stable/havana (rather then cherry-picking from master)

This should meet the stable branches goals of not introducing a whole bunch of changes (that update.py) would do while also maintaining an upstream first philosophy (oslo-incubator is our upstream for openstack/common).

Would still like to see oslo.messaging introduced as a dependency since we have all kinds of hassle updating rpc in the stable branches :)

Regards
-steve'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-06 18:34:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: No score

commit_message:
oslo: update the rpc module

- It now requires the versionutils module.
- We need to deal with the "allow_rpc_exception_modules" not
  including heat.common.exception

This actually *always* clears task_state when we set the vm_state to ERROR, not just in the build timeout case, right? I doubt that all of the possible states you can get to this way are ones where we want task_state reset. Further, I think you'll need to distinguish between a regular failure and a the timeout case in order to avoid just letting the user continue to hit the rebuild button for a situation that isn't going to change, right?"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-21 15:16:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Work In Progress

Dan, good point, I'll plan on changing _set_instance_error_state to take a task_state arg that defaults to the empty string for backwards compat (if empty string, don't pass it to instance_update). Then will only pass task_state=None from _check_instance_build_time which is the build timeout case."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-21 15:33:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Although on second thought, if the instance goes to ERROR state can you do anything with it besides delete or rebuild?  And rebuild expects the task_state to be None in that case, so it would fail w/o this change (if it failed in a non-timeout case).  Maybe I'm missing something though so I'll talk with Dan about it in IRC later."}, {'account_id': 5371, 'date': '2013-10-21 16:56:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

So it appears rebuild isn't allowed anyways unless the instance successfully spawns at least once. See this commit for details:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/99c51e34230394cadf0b82e364ea10c38e193979

This basically means this change is just a cosmetic state machine change. I don't think its worth doing anything here yet. Apparently the compute vm_state/task_state system is going to be re-visited in Icehouse."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2013-10-21 19:07:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-17 21:40:38.000000000', 'message': 'Reset task_state when instance fails to build due to timeout

When an instance fails to build due to a timeout the vm_state is set to
ERROR but the task_state is left as-is which can cause a problem when
trying to rebuild since the rebuild API expects the task_state to be
None.

This patch sets the task_state to None in the build failure case and
also cleans up the unit tests related to the _check_instance_build_time
method so that they are actually verifying the expected vm_state and
task_state values when the instance is updated.

Closes-Bug: #1241117

Change-Id: Ib384c84e2954bd303661386256053b3c1ad38239

commit_message:
Clean up test cases for compute.manager._check_instance_build_time

This patch cleans up the unit tests related to the
_check_instance_build_time method so that they are actually verifying
the expected vm_state value when the instance is updated.

This patch also removes the test_instance_build_timeout test case
since it was completely redundant with the other one modified
here. I checked the git history and both test cases were added
in the same commit which confirms that they weren't added for
different reasons, i.e. separate bug fixes/use cases.

Change-Id: Ib384c84e2954bd303661386256053b3c1ad38239

commit_message:
Add use existing vm option to boot-seed-vm

In CI testing, the environment in libvirt will already exist, adding
the --use-existing-vm option to indicate this and so it doesn't run
the virsh commands.

Still defaults to being configured.

Change-Id: If5c156c833509b2774e3e6c775498a4f84d8442b

commit_message:
Virtual Identity Providers CRUD operations.

    Implementation of CRUD operations for:
    *) Virtual Identity Providers
    *) Public keys tied to particular IdPs
    *) Protocols used to authenticate remote users (SAML, OpenId, etc)

Change-Id: I0d285fbcc6789f376a4ee250268ee6b307ad9a90
Implements: blueprint virtual-idp

commit_message:
Improve unit test coverage for Cisco plugin common code

Closes-Bug: #1190615

This fix improves the unit test coverage for the Cisco Nexus plugin
common modules (directory neutron/plugins/cisco/common) from:
--- cisco_credentials_v2.py 82%
--- cisco_faults.py 0%
--- config.py 84%
To:
--- cisco_credentials_v2.py 100%
--- cisco_faults.py 76%
--- config.py 100%

Change-Id: Id1ccfee1317309039fab83f622ced58efc3b2ae7

To use the decorator to skip a test if either caching is disabled
globally or in a specific section (e.g. assignment):

for the section because it is not defined, the decorator makes the
assumption caching is enabled for that section.

commit_message:
Allow caching to be disabled and tests still pass

Skip cache specific tests if caching is disabled.  Cache should only
be disabled to eliminate caching as an issue with tests, but in all
cases tests should pass in either configuration.  The default is
to use caching for all tests.

The caching options can be changed for testing purposes in the
keystone/tests/test_overrides.conf file.  The specific options
and sections that support caching can be located in the
configuration document in the section covering the caching layer.

Change-Id: I7848128aeaf3f578b89ab0b9201c45e00efecf11

commit_message:
Fix unable to add allow all IPv4/6 security group rule

Previously, if one tried to add a rule to allow all ingress ipv4 neutron
would respond that the rule was already part of the security group.
This happened as the filter for querying existing rules uses a wildcard for
remote_group_id thus returning a false match. This patch addresses
this issue.

Change-Id: I0320013a3869d25fb424995354721929465d2848
Closes-bug: #1252806

commit_message:
Do not concatenate localized strings

This makes it hard for translators to understand what is going
on. Use string formatting with kwargs expansion.

Change-Id: Ic9ad8bb4e3d9c32188f4175bb0359e268921696b

commit_message:
Fix a typo in log exception in the metering agent

This patch fixes a typo when there is a exception
when the agent try to invoke a method of the driver.

Change-Id: I4fcf19fa84f178348abfb3563bbfd52f0dfcc095
Closes-bug: #1256041
