commit_message:
port test_server_rescue into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I11e258e3f257348e74b4cf4d900c3f9b292e2539

[{'created': '2013-10-31 21:57:19.000000000', 'message': "Create thin lvm pools of correct size

This patch allocates 95% of a volume group's free space to the thin pool.

Ideally we would use 100% of the containing volume group by using the 100%VG
notation of lvcreate, but unfortunately this notation is not supported for thin
logical volumes.  Further, some amount of free space must remain in the volume
group for metadata for the contained logical volumes.  The exact amount depends
on how much volume sharing you expect.

Change-Id: Id461445780c1574db316ede0c0194736e71640d0
Closes-Bug: #1245909

This patch allocates 95% of a volume group's free space to the thin pool.

Ideally we would use 100% of the containing volume group by using the
100%VG notation of lvcreate, but unfortunately this notation is not
supported for thin logical volumes.

A reservation of 5% seems like a good place to start.  LVM uses the free
space to store metadata for volumes and snapshots.  The amount of space
necessary is entirely dependent on how many volumes and snapshots you
expect to have.  I intend on making this a tunable in the future.

Change-Id: Id461445780c1574db316ede0c0194736e71640d0
Closes-Bug: #1245909
"}, {'created': '2013-11-26 22:40:41.000000000', 'message': "LVM: Create thin pools of adequate size

Thin pools in LVM are quite different from volume groups or logical
volumes and their differences must be taken into account when providing
thin LVM support in Cinder.

When you create a thin pool, LVM actually creates 4 block devices.  You
can see this after thin pool creation with the following command:

    $ dmsetup ls

    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool       (253:4)
    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool-tpool (253:3)
    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool_tdata (253:2)
    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool_tmeta (253:1)

In the above command, a thin pool named 'volumes-1-pool' was created in
the 'volumes-1' volume group.  Despite this, the 'lvs' command will only
show one logical volume for the thin pool, which can be misleading if
you aren't aware of how thin pools are implemented.

When you create a thin pool, you specify on the command line a size for
the pool.  LVM will interpret this size as the amount of space requested
to store data blocks only.  In order to allow volume sharing and
snapshots, some amount of metadata must be reserved in addition to the
data request.  This amount is calculated by LVM internally and varies
depending on volume size and chunksize.  This is why one cannot simply
allocate 100% of a volume group to a thin pool - there must be some
remaining space for metadata or you will not be able to create volumes
and snapshots that are pool-backed.

This patch allocates 95% of a volume group's free space to the thin
pool.  By doing this, we allow LVM to successfully allocate a region for
metadata.  Additionally, any free space remaining will by dynamically
used by either data or metadata if capacity should become scarce.

The 95/5 split seems like a sane default.  This split can easily (and
probably should) be made user-configurable in the future if the user
expects an abnormal amount of volume sharing.

Change-Id: Id461445780c1574db316ede0c0194736e71640d0
Closes-Bug: #1245909

commit_message:
LVM: Create thin pools of adequate size

Thin pools in LVM are quite different from volume groups or logical
volumes and their differences must be taken into account when providing
thin LVM support in Cinder.

When you create a thin pool, LVM actually creates 4 block devices.  You
can see this after thin pool creation with the following command:

    $ dmsetup ls

    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool       (253:4)
    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool-tpool (253:3)
    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool_tdata (253:2)
    volumes--1-volumes--1--pool_tmeta (253:1)

In the above command, a thin pool named 'volumes-1-pool' was created in
the 'volumes-1' volume group.  Despite this, the 'lvs' command will only
show one logical volume for the thin pool, which can be misleading if
you aren't aware of how thin pools are implemented.

When you create a thin pool, you specify on the command line a size for
the pool.  LVM will interpret this size as the amount of space requested
to store data blocks only.  In order to allow volume sharing and
snapshots, some amount of metadata must be reserved in addition to the
data request.  This amount is calculated by LVM internally and varies
depending on volume size and chunksize.  This is why one cannot simply
allocate 100% of a volume group to a thin pool - there must be some
remaining space for metadata or you will not be able to create volumes
and snapshots that are pool-backed.

This patch allocates 95% of a volume group's free space to the thin
pool.  By doing this, we allow LVM to successfully allocate a region for
metadata.  Additionally, any free space remaining will by dynamically
used by either data or metadata if capacity should become scarce.

The 95/5 split seems like a sane default.  This split can easily (and
probably should) be made user-configurable in the future if the user
expects an abnormal amount of volume sharing.

Change-Id: Id461445780c1574db316ede0c0194736e71640d0
Closes-Bug: #1245909

commit_message:
Unittests added for glance/cmd/cache_manage.py

Related to blueprint glance-cmd+unittests

Unittests for all methods, that manage cache added:
* list_cached
* list_queued
* queue_image
* delete_cached_image
* delete_all_cached_images
* delete_queued_image
* delete_all_queued_images

Unittests for several internal methods added:
catch_error; env; create_options; parse_options; lookup_command

Change-Id: Id07bbecdc9877268a514e3a594699364dcc4618f

commit_message:
Add Flavor object

This patch adds the Flavor object and associated tests. It looks
mostly like the corresponding DB object, but without a nullable
flavorid attribute (which isn't actually optional). It also
makes a loadable 'projects' field with the associated project IDs
in it to avoid another object/interface for this simple thing.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects

Change-Id: Ib50a4efe874d6f19f5fc1178eb253ec8487f3808

commit_message:
Adding value for lock_path in configuration file

Now oslo code include new lockutils. According this code
if lock_path is not set in configuration file, will be
raised Error message.

So for updating lockutils in cinder project is needed
lock_path definition in configuration file.

Current patch fix problem for grenade test
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/48935/),
where after updating cinder.conf not include lock_path
option.

Change-Id: I77724cca3c3080dbd190e8823c7cb0aebb9d952d

commit_message:
Add atomic flavor access creation

This adds the ability to update the list of projects for a flavor
in a single go during create. This avoids a brief period of public
visibility between the time the flavor is created and assigned a
project.

Change-Id: I5c15c78809bfcb78e110c0d45dde8460a0ec98d6

commit_message:
port some server tests into nova v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: I4cf4187bb05ee48d867bff56ae12e6e48f615554

unit tests that are checking behavior of time-sensitive operations (eg, setting created_at, updated_at) should use the timeutils.set_time_override() method to manipulate system time within the test, rather than expecting minute time differences between python method calls.

Eg,

  def setUp(self):
    timeutils.set_time_override()
    self.addCleanup(timeutils.clear_time_override)

  def some_test(self):
    timeutils.set_time_override(t1)
    # do step 1
    timeutils.set_time_override(t2)
    # do step 2
    # validate the time difference between steps 1 and 2"}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-11-15 01:43:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Devananda, thanks for your comments, will use timeutils.set_time_override() to check time.'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-11-18 02:55:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: (2 inline comments)

'}, {'account_id': 8106, 'date': '2013-11-18 02:59:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15:

Do you have any idea, why our node.patch_json() method did not populate node.updated_at property? commit_message:
Expose created_at/updated_at properties in the REST API

Ironic client display created_at/updated_at values, but API does not
return these fields, so node-show display empty value always. With
this fix, we will add created_at/updated_at two fields into API base
class to enable all API to support these two fields, including node,
port and chassis now.

Closes-Bug: #1244072
Change-Id: I03f935902a86fac2f8fb58703c72ca0fda84843b

commit_message:
Clean up zombie processes on backup failure

Ensure that a SIGTERM is sent to the session leader of the process
group, so that all backup processes are terminated in case of a
FAILURE. This ensures that no zombie processes are left behind.

Closes bug 1253850

Change-Id: I4bd53c37923f83abe4c51deb95d740656ab21979

commit_message:
Added ability to pass custom command-line options to backup runner

Added a new DictOpt field "backup_runner_options" to the trove config
Custom command-line options for the backup runner can be passed in
through this

Closes-Bug: 1253849

Change-Id: I2ea45aa4899da4126776ef14a9cb2f0328a9e544

commit_message:
Add mocks for Pecan objects

This commit adds a fake objects which are used by pecan framework in controllers.
This allows to do write unit tests for Controller class without starting a pecan application.

Change-Id: Idd883fda93be4f7d28554c26902da0b9744f0bf1
Related-Bug: #1257449

commit_message:
host_href should include scheme

Barbican should not presuppose that host_href will be an HTTP endpoint.
This does not work when SSL is being used (ie. in the case there
haproxy is performing SSL termination for Barbican)

This change simply requires that host_href include the scheme to be
used when providing secret and/or order refs.

Change-Id: I22f6b13b693801322716d4c43ce8d508eca114dd
Closes-Bug: #1258598

_normalize_mac function when passed a unicode mac address. Also add test
to check that it works.

commit_message:
Add index to cover revoked token list

The individual expires and valid indexes do not fully cover the most
common query, which is the one that lists revoked tokens.

Change-Id: I112332b49dac148e5231b76f3399fe60174a702d
Partial-Bug: #1253755

Ok, even without going through the other patches ... I think this makes sense

Basically, in oslo.messaging we're currently just sticking the message in the listener's incoming queue and immediately acking it ... so this ack_on_error stuff isn't very useful

For reference, the history of this code is:

I308dd794b50966e3a189d31b2b51fdac36cd7d3a - initially we did reject() with ack_on_error=False

I6e820841b87eedb03318124e7d70be8da6970cc2 - then we switched to requeue()

Icc7a38b69dc0812f94475530f5573342d92a6590 - then we made sure to actually catch exceptions from callbacks spawned off in a greenthread

I43d47c2c8e03518221a17a2e9b0f342aa490e1bb - we talked about an exception based API to allow control over rejecting messages

I0a7f590d9bdbc158403b7212619a276c44e945f7 - this was a pretty broad patch which included passing delivery_info to the consumer and the other changes above"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-12-06 15:32:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: No score

commit_message:
Remove the partial implementation of ack_on_error

The ack_on_error is not used by the abstraction layer, and only the
rabbitmq implements it.

This commit remove this feature, and next commit will add a new way for
this.

Partial implements blueprint notification-subscriber-server

Change-Id: I17eb23f2e3e374630251576438011f186e5b2150

commit_message:
port test_quotas into v3 part1

This changeset only copies the v2 files into the appropriate v3
directories unchanged. This is being tried in order to make
reviewing of the porting easier as gerrit will display only what
is actually changed for v3 rather than entirely new files.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

commit_message:
Reduce max_age value of response.set_cookie.

Reduce the max_age value of the cookie that
holds the loagout_reason message. Reducing this
value reduce the chance to display the logout
reason message when a refresh is done or the
user login and logout inmediately.
It do not fix the bug, just reduce the
probability of ocurrence.

response.set_cookie('logout_reason', reason, max_age=5)

Change-Id: I8f8964af1a8b177b3c014032d374c28605e6c84b
Closes-Bug: #1231355

commit_message:
VMware: fix VM resize bug

The following operations would fail due to invalid references, either by name
or UUID:
    - resize
    - resize-confirm
    - resize-revert

Closes-bug: #1199954

(cherry picked from commit c586d635387e9baa3c0857afb56d05137fcddd7c)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_vmwareapi.py

Change-Id: I39b804ed3c0c57455547d9ece0ef779cf73a5926

commit_message:
Create a shared queue for QPID topic consumers

Fixes bug 1257293

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
ef406a21782134aeefb944f74b3f1a47d6169318

From the oslo-incubator commit:
When multiple RPC servers (consumers) are subscribed to the same RPC
topic, a single RPC request to that topic should be received by only
one of the consumers.  A bug in the QPID driver caused every consumer
to receive a copy of the RPC request.  This bug affects only Topology
version 2.  This patch will cause a single queue to be created for
each topic, and shared among all consumers of that topic.  This
results in each RPC request being received by only one consumer,
in turn across all the competing consumers.

Change-Id: I97c6eb5fe63322ab70716c63074818ff1b6ea82b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-05 22:27:55.000000000', 'message': 'Correct subscriber reconnection logic on QPID broker restart

Fixes bug 1251757

Picks up the fix from olso-incubation (i.e. sync limited to
this single fix for ease of backporting).

Change-Id: If966bb25e49b5837293a1bb181bbb02086599d81
'}, {'created': '2013-12-06 09:08:23.000000000', 'message': 'Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

Fixes bug 1251757

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
e227c0ed7e0ed1f9b8d029336f8aeb60e38c23df

From the oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Change-Id: If966bb25e49b5837293a1bb181bbb02086599d81
'}]
commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

Fixes bug 1251757

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
e227c0ed7e0ed1f9b8d029336f8aeb60e38c23df

From the oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Change-Id: If966bb25e49b5837293a1bb181bbb02086599d81

commit_message:
Move from inheritance HTTPClient in Ironic client

In the process of unification of the clients code we should use
composition to allow easier replacement with common HTTPClient.

Related to blueprint common-client-library-2

Change-Id: I9450c4d53f85e0dfabf9b1c49e001338d73b83f6

commit_message:
Enable rebooting in the client lib and cli

The client library should be able to request that a node be rebooted by
passing the "reboot" state to the API. This functionality should be
exposed in the CLI as well.

This depends on commit Ic13c046c621211d9c1533325812955233441d2da

Change-Id: I7954c02a3b5fd8f6caa574fd581f2ae3b0c3d422

Resource model with DB API

This patch involve necessary stuff for resource tracking in server
providers. There are Resource model and object with corresponding DB
API.

commit_message:
Add client side validation in Object upload page

The Object Upload page now has the Object Name field marked as
required with an HTML5 attribute. The goal is to execute the form
validation on client side to avoid the case when no Object Name
was provided, the file was uploaded and then the validation error
was shown. A reusable function was added that sets the html5
'required' attribute to django fields. A common approach for client
side validations is needed, but this custom fix will prevent
files to be uploaded unnecessarily.

Change-Id: I8b919b9978e8861702f9a5826a1bff848f40bdee
Closes-Bug: #1125232

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-29 08:46:55.000000000', 'message': "Make infrastructure engine pluggable

Right now we have a hard binding to savanna.service.instances
Since we want to introduce a new Heat engine and keep the old one
for a while, we need a way to switch between them depending on
user's decision. The change makes it possible to replace
savanna.service.instances with another implementation by changing
a single config parameter.

Change-Id: I3408529948537bef8338a4927f17fa6d47ec2b76
"}, {'created': '2013-12-02 12:21:27.000000000', 'message': "Make infrastructure engine pluggable

Right now we have a hard binding to savanna.service.instances
Since we want to introduce a new Heat engine and keep the old one
for a while, we need a way to switch between them depending on
user's decision. The change makes it possible to replace
savanna.service.instances with another implementation by changing
a single config parameter.

Additionally that change updates savanna.conf.sample-full which
was not done for some time.

Change-Id: I3408529948537bef8338a4927f17fa6d47ec2b76

commit_message:
Make infrastructure engine pluggable

Right now we have a hard binding to savanna.service.instances
Since we want to introduce a new Heat engine and keep the old one
for a while, we need a way to switch between them depending on
user's decision. The change makes it possible to replace
savanna.service.instances with another implementation by changing
a single config parameter.

Additionally that change updates savanna.conf.sample-full which
was not done for some time.

Implements blueprint infra-provisioning-extensions

Change-Id: I3408529948537bef8338a4927f17fa6d47ec2b76

> From Tempest should be able to run against any OpenStack cloud, be it a one node devstack install, a 20 node lxc cloud, or a 1000 node kvm cloud."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-15 19:00:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

mouad, each test class has "tenant isolation"

david, a few cases where I think this is good:

  1. someone could at any point add resources in setUpClass
  2. some previous test could leave resources in error/pending state
  3. anyone could run tempest disabling tenant isolation'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-11-17 16:08:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Cheers,'}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-11-18 10:06:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I saw a test results where these tests are failing ones:
 tempest.api.compute.admin.test_quotas.QuotasAdminTestJSON.test_create_server_when_cpu_quota_is_full[gate]

The tenant isolation is enabled.
Looks like somehow there is an unexpected vm in the 'newly' created tenant.

I thing would be better to find to the root cause than accepting the unexpected 1 vm sized resource allocation in the tenant."}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-11-18 13:09:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

It could be a previous test case that failed leaving a VM in error state (that consumed quota) that's why those test cases fail, nevertheless this test should not fail too. 

Assumption free is the king for robust code :)"}, {'account_id': 5803, 'date': '2013-11-25 18:06:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

My issue here is the quota test class is supposed to create new independent tenant, and it should not be effected by failures from any other test class.
If this test class has transitive failures related to any other test class it is bug either in tempest or in the application.
If everything is working correctly within the quotas test class scope no transitive failure expected.
No resourece expected in the tenant created by the quota test class ever.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-11-26 22:12:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

We're hitting this in Citrix's CI - but agreed that we probably should be able to find out why we've got VMs running or why the tenant ID is re-used rather than a fresh one created"}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-11-26 22:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I believe the issue here is test pollution - but I haven't yet identified where the pollution is coming from.
Failures that I have seen include running the test tempest.api.compute.admin.test.test_quotas.QuotasAdminTestXML.create_test_server as the first test.

This was a recent change (- and my guess is that it's conflicting with nosetest, but works fine for tox.
I assume this is with nosetest identifying all methods with "test" in them to run.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/53264/'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2013-11-26 23:08:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

See alternate fix at https://review.openstack.org/58645'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-27 20:06:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Do not merge

Attila said what I said, but better.'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-11-27 20:52:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@David: i think you are jumping conclusion here, i think Guilio gave already a detailed answer on when this is useful and i will repeat it here again:

- How about if allow_tenant_isolation is False ? Which is default by the way !
- How about if allow_tenant_reuse is True and i already run tempest and if fail with an instance in ERROR state ?
- How about writing pythonic code i.e. "In the face of ambiguity, refuse the temptation to guess" ?
- How about 7 lines of code that will make this test case test what it's suppose to test.

I already said that, but i would like to see a code free of assumption, i would like to see a code that consider edge case too, please, no "happy path" thinking because that's not real :)'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-27 21:03:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: No score

I think we are talking past each other. This test cannot run without separate tenants because it is setting the quota. There is a comment in the code about this but this test should really be skipped in the absence of tenant isolation. If this test is failing there is a bug somewhere else that it found. We seem to have different ideas of what makes a test robust. I will withdraw my -2 and others can comment.'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-27 21:20:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Mouad ON more thought I guess you must be running tempest sequentially and without tenant isolation since that seems to be the only circumstance where this matters. I have to admit that use case was far from my mind. Since we always run with tenant isolation in the gate that should probably be the default. So I guess there are two ways to look at the robustness of this test depending on how it is run.'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-11-28 12:14:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@David: That's true we are running tempest without tenant isolation and we have a good reason to do that (https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1242620), and i think we can learn for this that we can't relay on isolated tenant for each test case :)

Cheers,"}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-11-29 19:31:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

NOte that the network quota tests explicitly create a new tenant and set the quotas to zero. I really think we should just skip tests that are setting quotas if a new tenant cannot be created. We also have to make sure every test class can be run in parallel. So even if the suite as a whole is being run in a single tenant, it may be that some tests must use isolation or be skipped. How about we change this test to skip if isolation is prohibited?'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-02 09:42:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Is parallel execution of tempest relay on tenant isolation ? if so IMHO we should prohibit parallel run if tenant isolation is not enabled or maybe better find another way of doing parallel execution without relaying on tenant isolation.

The reason for this is that i would prefer tempest to not run at all by telling me that "i can't use such feature with such feature" instead of running and skipping **silently** test cases that may have detected bug/errors in my OpenStack deployment, and by silently i mean the tempest output is huge we don't expect people to read all of the skipped test case and why there was skipped.

Thoughts ?'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2013-12-05 20:04:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Do not merge

So I think there has been some confusion about what tenant isolation is and what is required for quota tests. If the allow_tenant_isolation option is set to True it creates a separate tenant (with user creds) for each tests class. This is a requirement for parallel testing otherwise we would have issues with resource conflicts. For example, things like list commands in tests would fail because we are creating and deleting resources in the same tenant so the list state couldn't be guaranteed at any point when running tests in parallel. This option however can't be turned on by default because they require admin credentials to properly be set ,which we obviously can't default to, and isn't a requirement for running tempest. Since parallel execution is handled by the test runner (which is independent and external from tempest) we can't actually enforce the coupling of running in parallel and tenant_isolation being enabled. We default to running in parallel because that is the most common use case (as most people run with admin and tenant isolation set to true) The solution for this disconnect is documentation, which admittedly based on this discussion we are clearly lacking right now.

Now the confusion point in this review is that tenant isolation and creating tenants in a test are separate and indepent things. If tenant isolation is turned off you are not prohibited from creating a tenant inside of a test. The only requirement for creating a tenant inside a test are admin credentials. (which should be checked and set to skip if they're not set) What both David and Attila are saying here is that this test should just create a new tenant and set the quota artificially low in that tenant to check that we are enforcing quotas properly. If there is a resource already present in that freshly created tenant causing a failure (which is what the bug indicates is happening) then you found a real bug that needs to be fixed. (which may be a tempest bug, or may be somewhere else) But, upping the quota is not the correct solution, and wouldn't necessarily be a long term fix."}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-12-05 20:55:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Note that the network quota test does create its own tenant. We should get rid of force_tenant_isolation and make the two tests that are using it do as Matt just said.'}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-05 22:12:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

This my last reply and i will abandon this patch, hopefully someone will picked up and do it the way you guys think it's right because i don't get it ...

> Since parallel execution is handled by the test runner (which is independent and external from tempest) we can't actually enforce the coupling of running in parallel and tenant_isolation being enabled.

Of course you can detect that the test runner is running your test cases in parallel, from the top of my head, how about using a simple file (in case of multiprocessing), enable_isolation = False, Each TestCase, check file <whatever> already exist and contain pid != current pid, Booom !!! But this is not our main issue.

> We default to running in parallel because that is the most common use case

Common use case to whom ? i don't run tempest in parallel i try it didn't work (i.e. a lot of error) didn't try it after that.

> The solution for this disconnect is documentation, which admittedly based on this discussion we are clearly lacking right now.

Totally agree, and probably a review of the design decision of which tempest was build on. (specially the tenant isolation part)

> The only requirement for creating a tenant inside a test are admin credentials.  

That's right and i will not give tempest admin credential if i run it in a production-like environment ! i hope you understand why :)

So like i said i don't get it, what i understood (which is weird) is that if i choose to run tempest with no tenant isolation and i didn't give it the admin credential, the quota tests will fail or do you want to skip them so that i (as user) will never know if i had a problem in my quota handling or no ! is this the long term solution ? 

What mostly bug me, is what the patch that i have supplied do wrong ? beside working in both when a fresh tenant is running this class or no.

Well anyway thanks for the review ...."}, {'account_id': 7073, 'date': '2013-12-05 22:12:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2013-12-06 14:54:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

And here is my last reply. This test will skip if you do not supply admin credentials, with or without your change. You need to be admin to change the quota. There are a bunch of TODOs from afazekas about how this test should just create a new tenant in setUpClass so that it could run even if tenant_isolation were turned off.

That said, it would be possible to have a version of this test along with a flag to enable it that created servers until the quota is reached.'}]

commit_message:
Simulate exhausted quotas by using the used limit

In case if an instance is already running setting the quota to 0 will fail
because we cannot set the quota to value less than the already used one, a
more sane value to set the quota to will be this total used value of this
quota.

Change-Id: I6b37479eac38d1be3677bb11a093b7eac356390e
Closes-Bug: #1247161

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-12-03 22:42:15.000000000', 'message': "Re-add havana support to the cert manager

A previous commit, 4bd2444c988741255bda4832a544d87d9bce4474, broke live
upgrades from havana to icehouse for the nova-cert service.  This commit
is one approach to restoring the ability.  It's a bit of a hack, though.

This works on the following assumptions:

1) We only care about supporting 1.latest version messages (what the
havana release would send)

2) We know that 1.latest is the same thing as version 2.0 of the API, so
the current manager implementing 2.x will always be compatible with
1.latest.

3) We can overlook the fact that technically we're advertising support
for all of 1.X, when really things will break if we received a message
older than 1.latest.

Change-Id: Ic2b4d8c86ab701086207e3be863c5a20e37ec452
"}, {'created': '2013-12-03 22:48:00.000000000', 'message': 'Re-add havana support to the cert manager

A previous commit, 4bd2444c988741255bda4832a544d87d9bce4474, broke live
upgrades from havana to icehouse for the nova-cert service.

The 1.0 and 2.0 cert rpc API are the exact same, with the exception of
the get_backdoor_port() method that was added in 1.1, and is no longer
used.  It was not used in the havana release either.

So, a 1.0 class that class straight into the class that supports 2.0 is
correct for this case.

Change-Id: Ic2b4d8c86ab701086207e3be863c5a20e37ec452
'}, {'created': '2013-12-03 22:52:01.000000000', 'message': 'Re-add havana support to the cert manager

A previous commit, 4bd2444c988741255bda4832a544d87d9bce4474, broke live
upgrades from havana to icehouse for the nova-cert service.

The 1.0 and 2.0 cert rpc API are the exact same, with the exception of
the get_backdoor_port() method that was added in 1.1, and is no longer
used.  It was not used in the havana release either.

So, a 1.0 class that calls straight into the class that supports 2.0 is
correct for this case.

Change-Id: Ic2b4d8c86ab701086207e3be863c5a20e37ec452
'}]
commit_message:
Re-add havana support to the cert manager

A previous commit, 4bd2444c988741255bda4832a544d87d9bce4474, broke live
upgrades from havana to icehouse for the nova-cert service.

The 1.0 and 2.0 cert rpc API are the exact same, with the exception of
the get_backdoor_port() method that was added in 1.1, and is no longer
used.  It was not used in the havana release either.

So, a 1.0 class that calls straight into the class that supports 2.0 is
correct for this case.

Change-Id: Ic2b4d8c86ab701086207e3be863c5a20e37ec452

commit_message:
Add Havana support back to the consoleauth manager

A previous commit, 02619bfd207d0d4f7e404203b539a20b3598cd80, removed
support for receiving Havana messages from the consoleauth manager.
This change restores that ability for the purposes of live upgrades from
Havana to Icehouse.

The latest messages sent by Havana are identical to the 2.0 version of
this rpc API.  As a result, the V1 proxy is a simple passthrough to the
main manager, which will retain compatibility with 2.0 throughout the
Icehouse release cycle.

Part of blueprint rpc-major-version-updates-icehouse

Change-Id: Ia320a7b1781acfa1cab0b37eb660059a68180041

commit_message:
Add Havana support back to the console manager

We are attempting to support live upgrades from Havana to Icehouse.  A
previous commit, 5dab438398f66020c205345a8dfbfc197d1acb28, removed
support from the console manager for receiving messages originating from
Havana.  Adding the support back is quite simple since the only change
from 1.x to 2.0 was removing a method (get_backdoor_port()).  Since the
Havana release does not actually send any messages for this method, it
can be left out of this copmatibility shim.

Part of blueprint rpc-manjor-version-updates-icehouse

Change-Id: I09c19f88ac720966e6cd95b5b0037ba7adb59609

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-10-16 21:20:09.000000000', 'message': 'Add V2 rpc api for conductor

Add support for the 2.0 conductor rpc API.  This commit retains compatibility
with the older 1.X API to allow continuous deployment without any downtime.

The v2 rev of this API was determined primarily by copying the current API
in nova.conductor.rpcapi.  That class always reflects the latest rev of the
API that is actually being used.

commit_message:
Add V2 rpc api for conductor

Add support for the 2.0 conductor rpc API.  This commit retains compatibility
with the older 1.X API to allow continuous deployment without any downtime.

The v2 rev of this API was determined primarily by copying the current API
in nova.conductor.rpcapi.  That class always reflects the latest rev of the
API that is actually being used.

UpgradeImpact - Deployments doing continuous deployment should follow this
process to upgrade without any downtime with the consoleauth service:

1) Set [upgrade_levels] conductor=havana in your config.

2) Upgrade to this commit.

3) Once everything has been upgraded, remove the entry in
[upgrade_levels] so that all rpc clients to the nova-conductor service
start sending the new 2.0 messages.

Part of blueprint rpc-major-version-updates-icehouse

Change-Id: I99a01338fdad4de408ff01dce18268916369783a

that all rpc clients to the nova-scheduler service start sending the new 3.0
messages.

commit_message:
Add v3 of scheduler rpc API

Add support for the 3.0 scheduler rpc API.  This commit retains compatibility
with the older 2.X API to allow continuous deployment without any downtime.

The v3 rev of this API was determined primarily by copying the current API in
nova.scheduler.rpcapi.  That class always reflects the latest rev of the API
that is actually being used.

UpgradeImpact - Deployments doing continuous deployment should follow this
process to upgrade without any downtime with the consoleauth service:

1) Set [upgrade_levels] scheduler=havana in your config.

2) Upgrade to this commit.

3) Once everything has been upgraded, remove the entry in [upgrade_levels] so
that all rpc clients to the nova-scheduler service start sending the new 3.0
messages.

Part of blueprint rpc-major-version-updates-icehouse

commit_message:
Corrected incorrect message when deleting port.

Updated the file /horizon/openstack_dashboard/dashboards/admin/
networks/ports/tables.py so it will give the correct error message
when trying to delete a port that is in use.This updated error
message will give the same information as when using the command-line.

Change-Id: I62c0fb1c5b9b073c0d083bddc45133d502b554be
Closes-Bug: #1251314

commit_message:
Add CentOS support

* As base image we use our own CentOS cloud image with preinstalled cloud-init
* Configuring that image
* Edit hadoop, mysql element for CentOS support and 'diskimage-create' script

Change-Id: If5570f31fd69c7cc809948dd2fa0249d00323f50

It's possible we end up creating ~/.ssh/authorized_keys in
install_dependencies, so we need to make sure it's permissions are set
to 0600.  Even if we didn't create the file, it's a change that can be
run without any pre-checks, as the previous "if" statement in the script

Change-Id: I70038954a06deb56c4d1d602cb436b5bb563ae40
'}]
commit_message:
Set correct permissions for ~/.ssh/authorized_keys

It's possible we end up creating ~/.ssh/authorized_keys in
install_dependencies, so we need to make sure it's permissions are set
to 0600.  Even if we didn't create the file, it's a change that can be
run without any pre-checks, as the previous "if" statement in the script
will create the file if it doesn't already exist.

Change-Id: I70038954a06deb56c4d1d602cb436b5bb563ae40

commit_message:
baremetal: Make volume driver use a correct source device

attach_volume() have to take the source device path from returning of
LibVirtVolumeDriver.connect_volume() rather than connection_info.

It also adds a test for attach_volume().

Change-Id: I3bee80560342104e2df614066301171624497a04
Closes-Bug: #1208707

commit_message:
Handle failures on update_dhcp_port

Ensure exceptions due to conflicting
state of network or subnet resources
are dealt with by the dhcp agent.

Closes-bug:  #1253344
Related-bug: #1243726

Change-Id: I4fd51442c034fabc91d5a3f065f4df98f5fad35b

commit_message:
Change evacuate test hostnames to preferable ones

The hostname grammar in RFC952 does not allow for underscores in
hostnames. However, some evacuate tests use them in each hostname.
This patch changes them to hyphens instead.

Change-Id: Id961e74a0bbeefbc843678edd74c02466b6d6885

'}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2013-09-12 15:49:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@GuoHui I don't think that the problem is in the block device mapping extension V2. In my understanding the problem is that in the make_server method when we attach the image node we are creating a selector and defining an ID for the image node:
# Attach image node
image = xmlutil.SubTemplateElement(elem, 'image', selector='image')
image.set('id')

When we don't have an image defined (for example for an instance booted from a volume) in the instance object we will have (the unit test is reproducing that scenario):
image: "",
so the serialization fails because it's trying to get the 'image id' from an empty object as the image selector is just an empty string.

As we can't have a kind of dynamic template my idea was to allowing to add an empty node with an empty attribute and to do that I modified the xmlutil.

I can see two other options here, to fix this:
1. I can remove in the Selector class (__call__ method) the catch of the TypeError exception and just return an empty string if the obj is an empty string.
That is a more specific check and avoids to miss some real TypeError exception
2. In the servers API extension, before returning details for the instance(s), we check that the request is requiring an XML response and if the image is not defined we add an empty id fields:
image : {id:""},

I prefer the option #1.

What do you think?

If you still think that the fix should be in some other area, can you provide more details, please?
Thanks'}, {'account_id': 7040, 'date': '2013-09-13 10:13:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Andrea,sorry for the late response, so a image id wan't given during the boot from volume? if so that might be a bug, I remember You must specify an image when booting from a volume, even though the specified image is not used. Otherwise, the Attempt to boot from volume - no image supplied error is returned."}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2013-09-17 09:56:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi GuoHui

sorry for the late response too :(
Actually there was a bug related to the boot from volume without an image ID as it was mandatory but now it is not any more:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1008622

In fact you can boot an instance from volume without specifying an image id and that works fine (if you are using a volume with a correct image), no error returned.

Thanks'}, {'account_id': 7040, 'date': '2013-09-17 11:12:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: No score

Hi GuoHui

I like your idea but it fixes just the id empty but then I have the original problem when the serialization is trying to create the links for the image. Maybe I misunderstood your suggestion but here what I've done:
in nova/api/openstack/compute/servers.py
 image.set('id', lambda x, True: x if x == '' else x['id'])
And I remvoed my change to the xmlutil.
Then I changed my test to add the make_links:
 xmlutil.make_links(image, 'links')
the test fails because of the original exception: it's trying to call a selector on an empty object.

Did I get correctly your suggestion?
I can't use the same approach (passing a callable) to the make_links method.

The other option to fix the problem is to modify the Selector class so as it checks if the obj is an empty string and in that case just return it.

Hi @GuoHui 

the links shouldn't exist if the image node is empty.
I am not hiding anything but I am simply following the same logic used in the xmlutil to deal with empty values that don't need to get rendered.
If you look at the TemplateElement.apply method you'll find that if an attribute has no value it's not included and this check works catching a KeyError exception that can be raised in the Selector.__call__.
My fix is just to add an additional exception that, in my opinion, is missed, so I am exactly applying/extending the same logic that is used there.
To have an empty attribute or not having value for a specific node is perfectly a valid scenario, in fact the same request in JSON works without including the empty attributes (in my case the image 'id') or node (in my case  links for the image node).

I am going to submit a new patch with the latest changes, please let me know what you think.

Last thing I want to clarity, the way to hard code catch keyerror and return '' is far less flexible from the way using EmptyStringSelector, first approach will making the xmlutil to lost the function to warning user which something doesn't exist, e.g. a typo of keyname, considering that we may need some flexibility, EmptyStringSelector was introduced here to make some flexibility *explicitly*, that's the huge difference though from grammar perspective, they are pretty same, thanks."}, {'account_id': 1865, 'date': '2013-09-30 10:02:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Hi GuoHui
I tried to ping you on IRC a couple of times with no joy :(
I am totally agree with you about the flexibility and that adding a new catch could hide some potential error.
I tried to apply your suggestions without introducing the new exception and it works for this specific case but it breaks 240+ tests. That is scaring me because one of the tests I checked (not all to be honest) shows me that something is going wrong with the serialization of the links, for example for the test nova.tests.api.openstack.compute.plugins.v3.test_flavors.FlavorsXMLSerializationTest.test_show
I have something like that:
flavor xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns="http://docs.openstack.org/compute/api/v1.1" name="asdf" ram="256" ephemeral="512" disabled="False" vcpus="" swap="512" disk="10" id="1"><atom:link/><atom:link/></flavor>

I am afraid that the change to the make_links needs a different approach and it might change the format of the generated output that could break the backward compatibility with what we have now.
So the situation is that at this moment we have a bug with the serialization of some empty values and adding a new exception is a short-term solution and surely not the perfect one. But, as I said, it follows the same logic used there.
For the long-term solution we need to find a more robust one that can allows more flexibility for dealing with different format of data.
My proposal is to allow this fix to go ahead and immediately create a blueprint to work on the long-term solution for icehouse release.
If I correctly understood, you worked on the serialization utility and I am really happy to work with you for finding a proper solution to this problem but for now we need to fix the original bug.
Unfortunately there are users/customers that love to use XML instead of JSON and this bug affects  several API calls.

What do you think?
Do you think we should raise this discussion on the mailing list?

Thanks for your time.
Andrea'}, {'account_id': 7040, 'date': '2013-10-07 02:47:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Fix empty selector XML bug

The XML serialization fails when it's trying to create a datum selector with no
values. In that case the obj is an empty string so the selection of datum from
it just fails.
Instead of raising an exception the fix is returning an empty string, that
allows to serialize Selector with an empty object.

Fixes bug 1223358

Change-Id: If5d564c9b037eb0a107f4688ffa1aceb5281dc42

commit_message:
freshen the LDAP support

* Build the base DN from a given domain name
* Remove all hard-coded names to allow configuration of base DN
* Fix manager DN (cn=Manager,dc=...)
* Add ldap init_ldap()
* Add support for clean.sh

Change-Id: Ieb69be9740653645b8e000574ad3fe59a0f97540

'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-12-02 13:06:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> most uses of metadata replace the Metadata class with a plain dict that eventually gets persisted during _store.

I don't quite follow this. Do you mean this is how it works now? Or in the future?

> This whole area needs refactoring - and that may be by replacing the Metadata class with plain dicts everywhere.

The problem with that is that it means going back to manually managing persistence. I always prefer code where you *can't* screw it up.


From your example, it seems like something like this would be equivalent, and would avoid adding complexity to the default Resource implementation:

  class ServerMetadata(Metadata):
      def __get__(self, resource, resource_class):
          if resource.properties.get('user_data_format') == 'SOFTWARE_CONFIG':
              return resource._deployments_to_metadata()
          else:
              return super(ServerMetadata, self).__get__(resource, resource_class)

      def __set__(self, resource, metadata):
          if resource.properties.get('user_data_format') != 'SOFTWARE_CONFIG':
              return super(ServerMetadata, self).__set__(resource, metadata)


  class Server(resource.Resource):
      metadata = ServerMetadata()

commit_message:
Property methods for resource metadata

For OS::Nova::Server which will build its metadata dynamically
based on currently available SoftwareDeployment resources.
This change makes it possible to:
* read and assign resource.metadata as before
* subclassses to override resource.metadata for building dynamically
* allowing access to the simple attribute based resource._metadata
  when necessary

partial blueprint: hot-software-config
Change-Id: Ifd7aa15dd58c96e6b9efafe6b4201a964e140d8d

commit_message:
Sync dhcp_agent.ini with the codes

Add an option item into dhcp_agent.ini to sync with the codes.
* Add ovs_integration_bridge in /etc/dhcp_agent.ini
* Add corresponding unit test

Change-Id: Ia78e7ca6c1fcbeca3e962f870a393e44183d719c
closes-Bug: #1256197

commit_message:
Change ID column of Event table to UUID

If you are using a public Heat you can use the event ID in
'heat event-list' to measure how much activity the service provider
has in their heat installation.

To avoid this, the Id column of the Event table was changed from
autoincremental integer to a uuid.

Added some unit tests in order to ensure that events with integer or
uuid id pass through the API, since we have a migration which will
leave behind integer ids.

Change-Id: I5693937b21acca6a3ddf6074f283a474684be3d2
Closes-Bug: #1249159

commit_message:
Mocking ryu plugin notifier in ryu plugin test

Previously RPC notifier is not mocked in ryu plugin test and the
plugin tries to send RPC notifications. It may interact with
impl_fake RPC set up in previous tests by other plugin
and sometimes leads to unexpected ovs-vsctl invoking.

Change-Id: I11714a160faa4d3ded7f312c39afba0b426ccd8a
Closes-Bug: #1255421
(cherry picked from commit dc2f567df3972465797d4d5b492ac1c243737cfe)

commit_message:
Avoid intermittent integrity error on alarm creation

Fixes bug 1255107

Previously, alarm created failed intermittently with the
sqlalchemy driver, due to the reliance on session merge to create
the project & user IDs if not already encountered.  This approach
conflicted with the strict foreign key constraints that were
added to the alarms table as an after-thought.

Now, we avoid the potential problem by creating the project and
user IDs explicitly.

Unfortunately, this cannot be tested via the scenario tests,
as there we use sqlite (the problematic migration does not
apply the foreign key constraints for that engine).

Change-Id: Ieaed676a0a68725242fadbf658646b874d6851ce
(cherry picked from commit b2b500c83cf5a81269c84a16f9a30ab7fa4c8ee6)

commit_message:
make record_metering_data concurrency safe

Recording metering might happen in parallel, and if two sqlalchemy
session try to create a source, a user, a project or a resource at the
same time, one of them fail with a IntegrityError.

This patch ensure the record_metering_data sqlalchemy session always
have the needed source, user, project and a resource by creating missing
obj in an other sqlalchemy session.

Fixes bug: #1237671

Change-Id: Ie8761ce1615c3142ad6ad2a400537f465f3bbf0a
(cherry picked from commit dd62f9ce0d8d5abac0fb34b0520515b6c4566c1f)

From oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted, RPC servers attempt to
re-connect. This re-connection process is not done correctly
for fanout subscriptions - two subscriptions are established
to the same fanout address.

Change-Id: I563db129e63817ad55165e318f164f06b141ee33
Fixes-Bug: 1251757
'}, {'created': '2013-12-05 19:34:42.000000000', 'message': 'Make fanout work on restart of QPID broker

From oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted, RPC servers attempt to
re-connect. This re-connection process is not done correctly
for fanout subscriptions - two subscriptions are established
to the same fanout address.

Change-Id: I563db129e63817ad55165e318f164f06b141ee33
Fixes-Bug: 1251757
'}, {'created': '2013-12-05 21:48:48.000000000', 'message': 'Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
e227c0ed7e0ed1f9b8d029336f8aeb60e38c23df

From the oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Change-Id: I563db129e63817ad55165e318f164f06b141ee33
Closes-Bug: 1251757
'}]
commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

This is a cherrypick of oslo-incubator:
e227c0ed7e0ed1f9b8d029336f8aeb60e38c23df

From the oslo-incubator bug:
When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Change-Id: I563db129e63817ad55165e318f164f06b141ee33
Closes-Bug: 1251757

commit_message:
Add db support for managing manila shares networking

Now that we have Neutron api we need an ability to export shares into
Neutron private subnets and save network info and networks-shares
association info.
Adds db models, migration, db api for neutron based implementation
of manila shares networking.

Implements bp join-tenant-network
Change-Id: Ia4f19cc1d5fe2b93ccf0a6805215560fc141b23b

commit_message:
Correct template path and metadata path in quick start

template path `elements/nova/os-config-applier' and metadata path
`elements/boot-stack/config.json' do not exist anymore in latest
`tripleo-image-elements' project. A workable quick start is
essentially important for beginners, so correct the two places.

Change-Id: I7d55a4c6766031d85e3a8ea1ba3a2afb2f802f46

[{'created': '2013-12-05 23:54:54.000000000', 'message': 'Create a shared queue for QPID topic consumers

When multiple RPC servers (consumers) are subscribed to the same RPC
topic, a single RPC request to that topic should be received by only
one of the consumers.  A bug in the QPID driver caused every consumer
to receive a copy of the RPC request.  This bug affects only Topology
version 2.  This patch will cause a single queue to be created for
each topic, and shared among all consumers of that topic.  This
results in each RPC request being received by only one consumer,
in turn across all the competing consumers.

Closes-Bug: #1257293
Change-Id: Id6af86f7fb536f3caff50bec4d5fde8a3ac1e83a
(cherry picked from commit ef406a21782134aeefb944f74b3f1a47d6169318)
'}]
commit_message:
Create a shared queue for QPID topic consumers

When multiple RPC servers (consumers) are subscribed to the same RPC
topic, a single RPC request to that topic should be received by only
one of the consumers.  A bug in the QPID driver caused every consumer
to receive a copy of the RPC request.  This bug affects only Topology
version 2.  This patch will cause a single queue to be created for
each topic, and shared among all consumers of that topic.  This
results in each RPC request being received by only one consumer,
in turn across all the competing consumers.

Closes-Bug: #1257293
Change-Id: Id6af86f7fb536f3caff50bec4d5fde8a3ac1e83a
(cherry picked from commit ef406a21782134aeefb944f74b3f1a47d6169318)

[{'created': '2013-12-05 16:36:33.000000000', 'message': 'Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

'}]
commit_message:
Properly reconnect subscribing clients when QPID broker restarts

When the QPID broker is restarted (or fails over), subscribed clients
will attempt to re-establish their connections.  In the case of fanout
subscriptions, this reconnection functionality is broken. For version
1 topologies, the clients attempt to reconnect twice to the same
exclusive address - which is illegal.  In the case of version 2
topologies, the address parsing is broken and an illegal address is
created on reconnect.  This fix avoids the problem by removing the
special-case reconnect code that manages UUID addresses; it is
unnecessary as the QPID broker will generate unique queue names
automatically when the clients reconnect.

Closes-bug: #1251757
Co-authored-by: Mark McLoughlin <markmc@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I6051fb503663bb8c7c5468db6bcde10f6cf1b318
(cherry picked from commit e227c0ed7e0ed1f9b8d029336f8aeb60e38c23df)

commit_message:
Missing asterisk in Launch Instance

Asterisk is missing for mandatory fields in security and networking tabs.

Every field which is mandatory or not,must be in "contributes".

For Selected Networks field,asterisk can be added in _update_networks.html.

Closes-Bug: #1252005
Change-Id: I25dafa7f595066f53517f385e075ac9b576dad6e

commit_message:
Change checkbox to radio when selecting form definition.

It has no sense to select more than one form definition while
composing a new Service Definition.

Change-Id: I459918acf75bd2fa17ed0950a59587913aadd8b2

commit_message:
Use 400 instead of 422 for invalid input in v3 servers core

We return 400 when input is invalid for v3 api. This patch fix
this case for servers core.

DocImpact

Change-Id: If802d4dcba6ed25f7e9cb9d568a3ffd78f0f6c68
Closes-Bug: 1251538

commit_message:
Let resource_tracker report right migration status

A shutoff instance can be resized, but resource_tracker only think
active instance is in migration state. This patch let it report
right migration status.

Closes-Bug: #1247610

Change-Id: Ic6ce9c7d8fdecaf812831eb302186133f0ee71b1

Clean up how test env variables are parsed

Oslo and cookiecutter and other projects were using
variable to parse test environment vaiables. Let us
do this in Nova

This is copied from 739627bf79619f8 Use cleaner version from
cookiecutter OpenStack template

Change-Id: I4c2b4072981985e7632fc775ffc98216fbfc0508

commit_message:
VMware: Always upload a snapshot as a preallocated disk

Currently, a snapshot operation always produces a preallocated
disk type. When the snapshot is uploaded to glance, the source
image metadata is uploaded with the new snapshot and then some
of the metadata properties are updated. The update doesn't
include the disk_type property, this can be problematic. If
the original image has a sparse disk type and a snapshot is
taken, then the snapshot which is a preallocated disk type is
uploaded to glance with the disk_type property set to sparse,
which creates a disk type mismatch and causes errors when a vm
is spawned from that snapshot. This patch addresses the issue
by correcting the image metadata used when uploading a snapshot
to glance.

Also, the image_upload function in vmwareapi/fake.py has been
modified to address the change. Any function call to
image_upload (from the unit tests) will assert that the
metadata for the image to be uploaded must have the disk_type
value to be preallocated.

Closes-Bug: 1247296
Change-Id: I71cfa8d4d1eb7911abb489153292fb0d1e614765

commit_message:
Fix limits v3 follow API v3 rules

* Add expected_errors decorator.
* Remove 'absolute_limit' from response, that already return by
extension quota_sets. And update api samples.

Partially implements bp nova-v3-api

Change-Id: Iea3ff494b8abed77fdc4b9e5e552784ed3733c34

commit_message:
Cleaned up and made revisions to doc

The letter "a" should not go before a vowel.
"An" goes before the word that starts with a vowel.
 The word in this case was "OpenStack".
I also added the plural version for IP Addresses.
Since we are referring to multiple IP Addresses,
we need to make sure we add "addresses" after IP.
also removed additional white space before colon

Change-Id: Ibd20045ffb83f1527007b3b4cef4763b305f724f

commit_message:
Cleaned up documentation

Added a period at end of sentence
Removed extra white space after the colon
IP used as plural I changed it to IP Addresses.
Originally corrected spelling for "Registring" but then removed
"Delivery and Registring" and changed sentence.

This looks pretty good!  Thanks for adding some functional coverage of caching.

I have a couple of minor questions/concerns.

1) Do you think it would be better to have this as integrations tests?  Markwash set up a good way to do those.  The main concern is that functional tests take a long time.  However I could see the cached one here going either way.

2) How do you feel about making a test_data_cache module?  I see downloads and uploads in function/v2/test_images.py so thus it is now clear to me how this modules is image_data specific thing.

3) While I think this is quite useful I am not sure that it fully addresses: https://code.launchpad.net/bugs/1199998.  For that bug I was hoping we could somehow automate all tests that download to download twice (as a means of testing the cache under various logical paths)."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-08-20 06:03:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:
